ę\•H®Śű1ęř¦a~†©¦ó* ŃN‹âO}ľ©ăš{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8dd4a0b6-8811-4d7d-84de-f2bcca6ecfb4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1be875fe5b85816c31a1b7c0952566bf47f9a01bc3157ae37f5b7d8c119069ed"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "leestoych", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-10-30", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia might be one of Yorgos' tamer films in recent times, but it's still quintessentially him.\n\nBugonia is one wild ride, and it works for two main reasons. The first is the incredible and convincing performances from Emma Stone andJesse Plemons (not to take away from Delbis). They bring the already sharp script to life, carrying every scene with intensity. The patient, quiet dialogue exchanges that build into sweeping orchestral crescendos really drive the bigger moments home.\n\nThe second reason Bugonia works so well is the subtle, almost subconscious doubts it plants in the viewer's mind. The film challenges our own perceptions of what's real, a clever way to keep the story engaging and prevent it from ever feeling sluggish.\n\nUltimately, though, it's the ending that defines the movie. It's a bold choice that will split audiences, some might find it ridiculous while others will applaud its courage. Personally, I think without that ending, Bugonia would've fallen into the realm of the generice thriller we've all seen before. Instead, it's audacious and unrestrained.\n\nBugonia had the nerve to be different, to challenge its audience and storytelling conventions. It's Yorgos at his best, and without a doubt, one of my favourites of the year."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "568a0196-636d-466d-9a7e-41b90edfde94", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c49fa038a061797f352aa9fd5831f0e042d860c707f4e3cd19bc14f35d5b7bab"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "julieshotmail", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-11", "title": null, "content": "Don't get me wrong, Emma Stone is terrific here, carrying that same cool, unreadable spark that Tilda Swinton built a career on, only with a younger, brighter edge. Stone has already collected two Oscars, though, and what really catches you off guard is Jesse Plemons, who turns in a performance so sharp and so unsettling that you keep thinking you've never quite seen him push himself like this.\n\n\"Bugonia\" eases in with what looks like a simple setup, just two men talking, one dominating the dialogue while the other tries to keep pace, and before you realize it the whole thing has shifted into a story that moves fast yet stays grounded enough to feel like something that could unfold a few blocks from where you live. I was hooked from the first scene and stayed that way nearly all the way through, though the ending lingers longer than it needs to, just enough to place it a step below \"Poor Things.\" Even so, it is unmistakably a Yorgos Lanthimos production, and it carries that same strange, irresistible flavor that makes his work so easy to sink into."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "40eea42c-910d-407b-b7fe-cf6bce829d84", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1922e85eba291ee4e8f3632aecde01e36f2ade7f2a771e6f75e3e01d0015ef7c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Ehi7", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-08-30", "title": null, "content": "This movie is a really good mix of genres in typical lanthimos styles, there's especially a lot of his sicked black humour as well as unexpected drama, horror and sci fi. Performances are all great but it's the finale that for me really elevates the movie. Funny, coherent, surprising, visually amazing.\n\nThe soundtrack was great too, looking forward to its general release to see the audience reaction."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3f66d98b-6060-4cac-9c7a-668f5131b17a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "cb3ca4cf636ae1dceae89519a11ded6e6f39d79f529286be5929728c6384de67"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Zzacarias", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-11-03", "title": null, "content": "How do I even start this? I think I need a second viewing. That sounds about right. This is such a good film, one of those where you completely lose track of time in the best way possible.\n\nThe story follows Teddy, a deeply disturbed man who's convinced that aliens have infiltrated Earth to control or destroy humanity. That belief becomes the core of the film: a critique of society's structure.\n\nThen there's Michelle, a CEO type with every stereotype you can imagine: the 4:30 a.m. Wake-ups, the cold discipline, the deep disregard for the people under her. It's comically illustrated when she says her workers should leave at 17:30 but then makes it blurry signaling this is something she doesn't actually expect.\n\nTeddy has this analogy about bees, how they work tirelessly for a queen who doesn't care about any of them individually. It's a simple idea, but the way the film uses it says a lot about hierarchy, power, and blind obedience.\n\nMisinformation and the Loops We Live In\n\nWe live surrounded by misinformation, but more than that, by these endless cycles that trap us inside our own ideas. Algorithms feed us what we already believe, keeping us engaged but also more entrenched. Teddy is the perfect example of that, we see him at work listening to conspiracy podcasts he calls \"research.\" It's all self-reinforcing, and it's frighteningly real.\n\nTrauma as Foundation\n\nAnother major theme here is trauma. From the start, we're left asking: why? Why does Teddy see the world this way? Why Michelle, specifically?\n\nIt slowly becomes clear that Teddy lives almost entirely isolated from others, his only real connection being Don, someone he mostly controls. His mother becomes the central figure in understanding his paranoia. She suffered irreversible damage from a medical trial run by Michelle's company, and that event planted the seeds of distrust in him from a young age.\n\nThere's a stunning black-and-white memory sequence that stood out to me, Michelle visits Teddy's family to \"apologize.\" We see Teddy as he is now, but he's clutching to his mother on an hospital bed like a balloon, signaling that he was a child during this memory. It's a subtle, haunting way of showing how that trauma froze him in time. Later, with Casey the cop (played in a great cameo by Starvos), we start to understand that Teddy's trauma goes even deeper probably involving some kind of sexual abuse. It's heavy, but it gives context to his warped worldview.\n\nManipulation and Power\n\nManipulation runs through everything in Bugonia. Even in what we call \"normal\" society, manipulation is a fundamental part of how we function, it's how people achieve their needs or maintain control.\n\nWe see this clearly with Michelle's corporate behavior, but also with Teddy's control over Don. Don clearly doesn't want to go as far as they do (the chemical castration scene says it all) but Teddy pushes him with emotional manipulation. It's darkly ironic that Teddy, who rails against power structures, ends up mimicking them himself. He becomes, unknowingly, the very \"queen\" he claims to hate.\n\nMichelle never really manages to manipulate Teddy into believing she's an alien. The shift happens almost by accident when the electrocution test doesn't kill her, which Teddy interprets as proof she's a \"royal.\" That one twist of luck seals both their fates.\n\nThe Spiral\n\nThe first two acts are fantastic, tense, darkly funny, layered but the third act takes things to another level.\n\nDon's death hits hard. You feel his growing awareness that they've gone too far, that none of this was ever real. Teddy, realizing both Casey and Don are dead, descends into a frantic, unstable state. Michelle seizes the moment, manipulating him into killing his own mother so she can escape. But in a brilliant touch, Michelle's escape fails because she's too injured to climb the stairs and notices what appears to be a door.\n\nBehind it: the true horror. She isn't the first. Teddy's done this before. The walls are lined with past victims, and that revelation shatters her remaining grip on reality.\n\nWhen Teddy returns, both of them are in full panic, not just physical chaos but psychological collapse. I loved how Yorgos shows this through movement: Michelle, once too injured to climb stairs, suddenly sprints up them. It's a visual cue that she's beginning to detach from reality.\n\nWhen the story returns to the company, everything falls into place. Michelle's plan is clear. She'll entrap Teddy and escape. The \"teleportation\" scene is so unexpected it just left me baffled.\n\nThe Ending and What It Means\n\nAfter Michelle is struck in the head, she wakes up in an ambulance, panicked, and rushes back to the office. She's clutching the calculator, trying to reach the \"mothership\" before the moon cycle ends and somehow, it works.\n\nBut this isn't sci-fi logic, it's psychological breakdown. She's in shock, her mind splintered by trauma. The ship we see mirrors Teddy's own drawings. When she decides to \"erase\" humanity, bursting the atmosphere (with the darkly funny reveal that the planet is flat) it's not literal, it's symbolic. Animals survive, suggesting that she's rejecting humanity itself, not life.\n\nTo me, it's not about whether Michelle is an alien. She's not. Her final act feels like a collapse of empathy and meaning, a commentary on how deeply broken the structures we live in really are.\n\nThe Bigger Picture\n\nThis movie's critique feels painfully real when you think of corporations like Amazon, boasting $9.5 billion in pre-tax profits while firing unionized drivers and running aggressive union-busting campaigns. Remember the news drivers were forced to urinate in bottles to meet impossible quotas?\n\nThat's Bugonia's point: we don't have to live like this. The system is built on exploitation dressed up as efficiency, and it runs on manipulation disguised as ambition.\n\nFinal Thoughts\n\nIt's clear by now that I absolutely loved this film. Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons are extraordinary, they channel both intensity and fragility so well. The sound design, cinematography, and direction are impeccable.\n\nThank you, Yorgos, for another art piece."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "66bfd6ca-39ec-4b04-88b6-506cac34f3c9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "729e03330d14c04c737dd741f51c3f0aefea8fee1064ff13d3dbd163e5a0e3cd"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "shakespeare62", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-02", "title": null, "content": "Lanthimos strikes again! And it's another masterpiece. Black Comedy, Satire, Social critic on internet conspiracy theories, weird, absurd, witty, bloody and last but not least a nihilistic comment on mankind working on its own extinction.\n\nAnd what an intelligent screenplay it is! And all in all an exciting and entertaining movie with surprising twists. How many times can you leave the theatre feeling refreshed and inspired, because you know you have just watched something you have never seen on a screen before? Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons deliver great performances, on top of their skills. It's such a pleasure to watch actors with their depth and intensity.\n\nI loved the whole experience, it's a brilliant movie, strongly recommended."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "fb659bf3-ac5d-4ce5-b9a9-d9d541dae676", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "acc40694868d8497b22ce03ce55c2badad32224631d4ccdb415cc591e4bea55a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "imdbrent", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-12", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is well acted and has some nice interior and exterior shots in the first three acts.\n\nOther than that, it has a very mediocre plot that tries too hard during the last act. It is actually laughable what the twist is and the costume, set design and overall aesthetic looks bad during this post-climatic scene.\n\nI tried to explain the plot of the movie to a friend and it just sounded dumb, because it is.\n\nAnother gripe is the classic trope of lack of security causing the entire movie to happen.\n\nAnother overrated Lanthimos movie that is basically a C-tier Black Mirror episode.\n\n5.5/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9162317d-adbd-444b-9c49-d3efa75342bc", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2e1695a78bc39a1790187e29050c183e9cea088498d312c6d7077c0eb1987fbf"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "MirceaT-71", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-10-16", "title": null, "content": "Watching *Bugonia* felt strange in the best possible way. Lanthimos throws you into a world where nothing feels entirely normal - the rules are odd, people react in unpredictable ways, and yet something about all this chaos feels oddly familiar. You laugh, but there's always tension underneath it, like you're waiting for something to go wrong. The emotions hit harder than expected, even in moments that seem absurd on paper.\n\nThe story follows two conspiracy-obsessed men who kidnap Michele (played by Emma Stone), a corporate figure they believe is an alien trying to destroy Earth. It sounds ridiculous - and it is - but Lanthimos uses that absurdity to dig into paranoia, power, and the strange ways people cling to belief when faced with uncertainty.\n\nVisually, the film looks beautiful and a bit unsettling. Shooting on 35mm gives it texture - the kind of imperfections, shadows, and lighting you don't get with digital. It makes the world feel alive, slightly out of sync, and that's exactly what this story needs. The camera work feels intentional without being flashy, every frame adding to the unease.\n\nThe tone is darkly funny but emotionally sharp. Lanthimos doesn't offer easy answers or explanations. He just builds tension through behavior - through silence, through glances, through moments that should be funny but end up being uncomfortable. Emma Stone stands out; she plays Michele with a mix of calm control and quiet menace that holds the film together.\n\nIt's one of those films that doesn't fully explain itself, and maybe that's the point. You either go along with its strange rhythm or you don't. For me, it worked - not because everything made sense, but because it felt honest in its chaos. Lanthimos doesn't tell you what to think, he just lets the madness unfold, and somehow, that's what makes it stick.\n\n**Verdict:** 9/10 - not as tight as *The Favourite*, but easily Lanthimos's boldest and most unpredictable work since *The Lobster*.\n\n."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a5b7d4e0-c4af-449e-ade1-3614cf544610", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f22e77712bd9d9dd5d275bd1e1af9ae0a04eb6cc9877c0a84376b79ee50819d4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "marcussanders-72942", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-09", "title": null, "content": "If you're heard anything about Bugonia then chances are you know the premise, so I won't talk about the plot too much.\n\nAll I'll say is that for 90 minutes or so, Bugonia is a lean, taut, darkly satirical thriller centred on a couple of outstanding performances by Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons - and if the movie had ended after those 90 minutes I'd probably be giving this 8 out of 10.\n\nAs it happens, the third act had a twist which wasn't particularly shocking or surprising, and it all ended on a rather dour note which I personally didn't enjoy. If there was a message the filmmakers were trying to convey, it was less profound than profoundly despressing.\n\nStill, it's not a movie I'll be forgetting any time soon so I'll give them that, even if I don't see myself re-watching it for a good long while."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "392d08fb-4e03-4531-be75-bba8accc5a1d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "eddcfedaef307c0583293fc6d2fe356a6c66590f78ddd4ff13aec2a7f811f3ba"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "masonsaul", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-10-13", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is a classic Yorgos Lanthimos movie as it examines the darkest parts of human nature in a characteristically darkly comedic fashion but it also offers something different when it operates as a tense thriller. It's a neatly structured film that only gets better once things properly escalate in a genuinely shocking way and it reaches a satisfying conclusion. This is another recent release which really feels of the moment.\n\nJesse Plemons is amazing by being fully committed to the naivety of his character which makes him equally threatening and gullible. Emma Stone is effortlessly confident and funny as she slowly begins to control the situation, continuing her winning collaboration with Yorgos in a way that shows her full potential once again. It's the constantly shifting power play between these two that keeps it so investing and unpredictable.\n\nDirector Yorgos Lanthimos delivers one of his strongest films to date where the trademark surrealism feels more appropriate thanks to the premise whilst working with some of his most consistent collaborators behind the camera. Robbie Ryan's cinematography knows how to make each scene look beautiful and surreal at the same time, complimented by Jerskin Fendrix's suitably paranoid score ensuring everything feels ominous when needed."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "91dbc474-12be-493b-a7da-795972b2f0bb", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f803e0c0a5df5087026ef218748246b5febac0e98cb0df255f30b5ca23455e00"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Felix-Wackenhuth", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-18", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia was like a rollercoaster.\n\nWatched it with a friend and we where on the edge of our seats the entire movie just stunned of the dialogue and how everything would play out.\n\nI know Lanthimos often got a ace up hes sleve but was this really the right way to use it? You probably know what I am talking about, was the Alien supernatural ending really necessary?\n\nI often prefer movies that tend to keep things simple and relatable. The core idea of the movie being about a kidnaping is a good foundation but what I think could have worked out is Emma stones character getting further under the skin of her intruders. The ending would have stayed impactful if it just skipped everything with the supernatural. Watching the movie thinking everything is real and then turning your mind upside down looses the core of the movie."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0015fc28-fd11-4d12-9569-c8a48001df72", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f4416b36ab97f1675aa6d2c91d42a910cede0dff44b02abd12f339912baad5f9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "janbuchen", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-05", "title": null, "content": "Not for everyone, but definitely for me! To start, the acting was unbelievable from the three main characters. Emma Stone was amazing, and Jesse Plemons and the actor who plays his cousin are just outstanding. The hair and makeup were very creative - from bald on Emma, to HELP - PLEASE GET THIS MAN SOME SHAMPOO! The story was the fun part - who doesn't like twists, turns, ups, downs and inside outs??? This was just a fun movie that made me want to see it a couple more times, just like Poor Things. BRAVO!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4c3b1a43-d316-4a3c-a52b-7b164386c78e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2f0e51ebdc76f5e500994e397c427046f51475686ff1dc4f3171ea0c98ec9214"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "costa-cola", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-08-29", "title": null, "content": "Director Yorgos Lanthimos brings us back exactly to where he left us with Kinds of Kindness: American suburbs, conspiracy theories. Bugonia feels like the fourth episode of his anthology. Who knows, it might even be.\n\nBugonia is a remake of the Korean movie Saving the Green Planet.\n\nIt tells the story of two cousins, Teddy and Donny, who live by themselves. Teddy, the sharper one, feeds himself and his cousin with conspiracy theories, while Donny (portrayed with clear neurodivergent traits) follows him with devotion.\n\nThey kidnap CEO Emma Stone, accusing her of being an Andromeda alien, and demand that she contact her colleagues so they can leave Earth and let it be at peace again - bringing back, among other things, the well-being of bees.\n\nWe quickly realize that Teddy has been personally affected by Emma Stone's company: his mother is still in an induced coma because of the drugs she took from them. It becomes clear that Teddy's delusions are also driven by these personal implications.\n\nTeddy (and Donny, secondarily) is the typical example of the isolated internet addict: spending excessive time online and turning into an irrational, disconnected being. In contrast, Emma Stone is shown at the beginning of the movie creating promotional material for her company, where the script includes the word \"diversity\" more than X times. The movie wants to show us the two sides of today's America, and how their clash can only result in extreme and dangerous encounters.\n\nThe theme is nothing new and perhaps lacks a more impactful message. There is, however, an interesting analogy between bees (alien-like creatures operating efficiently and without distracting human feelings) and humans, who - when seen from an alien perspective - seem to make the most irrational decisions: killing each other through wars, destroying our own habitat, or wasting time and attention on futilities (a theme also reflected in the final scene). But the underlying message doesn't seem to be the movie's main concern; its real value lies in the execution.\n\nBugonia does a terrific job of entertaining the audience. It knows when to be funny and when to build tension. The dramatic music choices are particularly effective and give pace to the movie. The audience is on edge the whole way, constantly asking: \"What if she really is an alien?\" The movie plays with this doubt and even makes fun of us for believing it could be true - subtly reminding us we may not be in the best position to mock conspiracy theories.\n\nThe movie falls short in its final minutes, when it is clumsily revealed that the CEO was, in fact, an alien. While this seems intended to be either surprising or funny, it lands as neither. By then, the audience has already entertained the possibility several times and dismissed it, because it would make little sense logically or dramatically. Nevertheless, it seems Yorgos Lanthimos either decided to follow the original story beyond what best served this film (by keeping that final scene), or he simply chose to \"prank\" the audience with an unsatisfying finale. But if the prank isn't funny, is it really worth it?"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3266d3c6-51dd-42eb-b0a7-20833efefa43", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6bbce6377252c3d61b8882d64c4eec08190c19b5326a8b09e466b12e571836fd"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Papaya_Horror", "rating": 5, "date": "2025-10-26", "title": null, "content": "22 years later, Yorgos Lanthimos dares to remake the 2003 Korean masterpiece \"Save the Green Planet!\" by Jang Joon-hwan.\n\nDespite my love for Lanthimos, this film, unfortunately, doesn't quite deliver the same gut-wrenching agony as the original-even though the execution is technically stunning. I'm genuinely torn about how to feel about it.\n\nLet's start by saying: it's not a bad film, but it's not a great one either. This time, I'll take a slightly different approach-comparing both films to see where each shines and falters, while keeping things spoiler-free.\n\nThe first thing you'll notice-if you've seen both versions-is the colour palette. \"Save the Green Planet!\" embraces dark greens and blues, while \"Bugonia\" opts for rich oranges and reds.\n\nBoth are effective in building a sense of threat, but-and that's my opinion-the green hues serve the story better. The orange, however, feels perfectly aligned with Lanthimos's current aesthetic.\n\nKeeping the same tones as the original would have felt like pure imitation, so going for a warmer colors make it feel more contemporary and ominous.\n\nBoth films run around two hours, yet \"Bugonia\" lost me halfway through-and by \"lost\", I mean I nearly dozed off. It's weighed down by dialogue that easily slips into rhetoric and monotony, whereas \"Save the Green Planet!\" balances its dialogue with bursts of violent action.\n\n\"Save the Green Planet!\" dances along the edge of psychological horror and physical discomfort, even flirting with torture territory. \"Bugonia\"has its moments of violence and splatter, but never reaches the same level of unsettling intensity.\n\nA remake shouldn't be a carbon copy of its source, and in that sense, Lanthimos leaves his unmistakable Hollywood fingerprint. Still, Joon-hwan's film feels far more decayed and dystopian-a film of a time, the 2000s-when politically correct wasn't yet an invisible law.\n\nHowever, \"Bugonia\" is more polished, more accessible, clearly tailored for a broader audience. That accessibility also reshapes its perspective-and that's where the two directors diverge most.\n\nThe direction, of course, differs greatly-two directors, two cultural lenses. Joon-hwan thrives in the grit and chaos of the working class, while Lanthimos prefers the stylised decay of wealth.\n\nBoth handle the class divide with flair, but through entirely different textures.\n\nPerformance-wise, both casts are solid. Emma Stone's portrayal of Michelle arguably fits better for the role; her shaved head and eerie makeup sharpen her ambiguity.\n\nConversely, Baek Yoon-shik's Kang Man-shik lacks her magnetism but compensates with raw, unsettling force-his maleness also allows Joon-hwan to push certain boundaries further.\n\nIt's not a gender issue, but a difference in how far each director dares to go within their respective cinematic climates.\n\nInterestingly, the gender swap extends beyond the lead conspirator. In \"Save the Green Planet!,\" the abettor is a girl, Su-ni (Hwang Jung-min), whereas in \"Bugonia\" it's a boy, Don (Aidan Delbis).\n\nThis shift subtly changes the emotional dynamics, even though some of the empathy between captor and captive remains intact.\n\nAs for the mastermind behind the abduction: Teddy, played by Jesse Plemons-an actor I'd protect at all costs-feels a bit muted here. In contrast, Shin Ha-kyun's Lee Byeong-gu in the original radiates psychotic energy and conviction.\n\nThe endings have sparked endless online debates, and truthfully, both work within their respective worlds. They hit different emotional notes but leave the same pit in your stomach.\n\nBoth films hold a mirror to our species-fractured, hopeful, and cruel, highlighting the same uncomfortable question about humanity that feels increasingly urgent today. Watch both, then decide for yourself.\n\nAs for me? My allegiance remains clear-I'm still all in to \"Save the Green Planet!\" Sorry, Lanthimos, but this time you didn't quite abduct me."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d0bc027a-6046-4972-9e9d-7de407cd9d10", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2b4b8774d4086e5067165510e8a8348a76b4b301157611a7f2916c997a12f529"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Brina223", "rating": null, "date": "2025-12-01", "title": null, "content": "Yorgos Lanthimos is back doing his usual weird thing with Bugonia. It's a remake of Save the Green Planet!, but feels colder and more deliberately uncomfortable.\n\nEmma Stone is chilling as a boss-lady, and Jesse Plemons is incredible as the paranoid conspiracy-theorist unshaken in his conviction that she's an alien. The film is basically just them facing off, a true acting masterclass. It keeps you guessing till the very end.\n\nDo not go in expecting a run-of-the-mill sci-fi action thriller. There are no laser battles or such business here. This is a claustrophobic psychological duel and pitch-black satire. If you want high-octane explosions, look elsewhere. If you don't mind feeling a bit sick and confused by the end, it's for you."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cd2aa94d-ac97-4e43-8804-b4559a85892f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c9604acee72dac4c5331397b74a3b88d48583a9544d805304b8f6336fbe82e77"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "nick8-8", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-29", "title": null, "content": "The film turned out no worse than the Korean version, which is already impressive on its own.\n\nEmma Stone and Jesse Plemons once again deliver outstanding performances.\n\nWhat we get is a sharp satire that makes you wonder: maybe conspiracy believers are simply broken by the real world? Maybe that's why they retreat into fantasies, searching for secrets that don't actually exist, just to justify their own problems?\n\nThe ending raises a question: can we ever be as organized as bees? Or are we destined to remain fragmented and harm one another? Does a perfect version of humanity even exist?\n\nLanthimos once again does not disappoint."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "804b749d-6dd5-45ed-932a-658248cda53a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "571dbe20f64336b17f629c6828009dac916ce68de54b73686ee0bfb322db6e36"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Couchkik20", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-10-11", "title": null, "content": "London Film Festival review\n\nFor a moment BUGONIA is like watching \"Misery\" or \"Funny Games\" through the lens of 1950s Hollywood dystopian paranoia films. Yorgos follows the sadistic path he started in The Killing of a Sacred Deer and Kinds Of Kindness playing with Kubrick-like visuals and sounds to deliver a fairly straightforward cynical fable until it's not.\n\nEmma and Jesse explore a violent theatricality and beautiful expressionism to great success. Both are harrowing and spectacular (this is Plemons best part ever) but are also limited by the linearity of it all. The last act reconnects Lanthimos with his subversive, unpredictable and absurd poetry but I guess Media, Politics and Truths are this year's true topics. Not surprising this film shares common grounds with Eddington.\n\nI wanted to love it but I just really really liked it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "90c8aa2e-cc6f-44fa-b06e-79d5f5712b6e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2015e497e2508c072648fa76cb93c57e0ab822b1656596f3df6a183b4548abd7"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Someguy95", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-10-28", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia: \"Ox Birth\" A fictional method where bees are spontaneously generated from an Ox's carcass.\n\nBugonia is a movie focusing of human alienation, in terms of privilege on both ends of the extreme and human self-destruction. The story centers on Teddy Gatz (Jesse Plemons), a beekeeper and alien conspiracy theorist who has decided he must save the world. Teddy, who lives in an isolated family home with his simple and reluctant cousin/accomplice, Don, has become alienated, living solely in a world of online quackery. Teddy believes an overarching conspiracy by the alien race, the Andromedins, is the true cause of suffering, rather than corporate greed.\n\nThey kidnap Michelle Fuller (Emma Stone), the head of a PR-savvy biomedical conglomerate. Michelle is characterized by her use of corporate jargon and a veneer of accountability to cover business interests. Teddy's plan is to use Michelle as a hostage/ambassador to contact the Andromedins and negotiate a settlement for them to leave Earth alone from their secret control. The conflict however has a personal root, Michelle was heading the failed clinical trial that resulted in Teddy's mother's coma, questioning if his intention is \"human salvation\" or self-serving revenge.\n\nMichelle constantly balances between horribly alien and weirdly human. Shaving her hair and covering her in cream make her appear an otherworldly creature, yet her singing, crying, and screaming are all too human. She admits to Teddy that she sees she has become a person she swore she would never be through her corporate cover ups, recognizing her own alien elements in seeking corporate over human interests.\n\nThe dialogue between them is sharp, hilarious and thought provoking. Michelle's attempts to psychologically control Teddy are shattered when he reveals his (and Don's) chemical castration to limit their attraction, shocking her into understanding their fanaticism. Michelle is then forced to conform to his delusion, spinning tales of Atlantis and a Yacoubian genetic plot to fit her role as an alien royal.\n\nThe turning point occurs when Don self-exits. Don functions as an audience stand in and the moderating presence, whose humanity and disgust with the torture constantly strain his love for Teddy. Without Don, the conflict becomes to the death. The violence escalates with the killing of a cop, maiming, the killing of Teddy's comatose mother with antifreeze, and the final infiltration of Michelle's workplace with Don's body in the back. The humanity Teddy sought to portray is cast aside, and Michelle's survival depends on leaning further into her alienating qualities.\n\nThe movie is fantastic up through the ambulance scene, but the ending creates a massive tonal shift. The film resolves the ambiguity, confirming that Teddy was right (Michelle was a real alien). In an Orphean tragedy, He also leads humanity to its doom as he represents human fatalism at its worst through his violence and serial murder to the mostly benevolent Andromedins. Michelle returns to the mothership and, after lamenting about being corrupted, convinces them to end the human experiment. Everyone dies as humanity is deemed self-destructive and irredeemable.\n\nHad the film retained the element of ambiguity (leaving Michelle in uncertainty) on what dilutes our humanity and makes us alien, it would have been much stronger. Yet ultimately it is a gorgeous and deviously funny film well worth the runtime."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1dc4c134-924d-4557-9bc2-c73db1bbbd81", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c87d4315765cdf3ea4be0d0653beafff3c5cf84734b812010ccd3efa975fa8fe"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "housermichael", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-10-24", "title": null, "content": "I am a big fan of Yorgos Lanthimos as a director from his previous films like \"Poor Things\" and \"Kinds of Kindness\", both of which I think are among the best movies of recent years. I also liked \"The Lobster\".\n\nNow he is back with his former collaborators, actors Jesse Plemons and Emma Stone in the new film \"Bugonia\", which I think is another contender for best film of the year.\n\nThe story is about two men who kidnap a CEO because they think she is an alien trying to destroy the earth. Emma Stone plays the CEO and Jesse Plemons plays one of the kidnappers.\n\nThey both give excellent performances worthy of an Academy Award nomination. And the film is superbly shot by the cinematographer Robbie Ryan. I think this is the most beautifully photographed movie I have seen all year. And the production design and the music score are both very good. I recommend this movie to anyone who has enjoyed the previous work of Yorgos Lanthimos. A bizarre but enjoyable film."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3f591e83-4ae7-4f78-99ab-25363fde195a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "621cd84382bd75b99a819aa7ed8d5bdd62b7ef7eed5f5806598510ce2eac3321"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "pjpj-72890", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-10-10", "title": null, "content": "An unconventional yet both intriguing and entertaining movie. The absurd and unsatisfying ending almost ruined it for me though. The finale left me with a sentiment of being mocked by the director in charge. Unseeing the final 15 minutes would have resulted in a higher rating as far as I'm concerned."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1af5d4f1-81ed-49f9-87d2-24f49e21843f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "af370303ff15bccbb02812f72f64cc6f94bcd7550b76b0e263a052ac5b559329"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "killercola", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-01-03", "title": null, "content": "I did not expect this to be the best movie I would see in 2025. Emma Stone is in top form but Jesse Plemons steals the show. He should win an Oscar for this. And this will be a movie you will want to rewatch. I won't say why but you will understand after you watch it the first time. Absolute gem of a film and the most original story in years. Ignore the middling reviews. It's likely this movie will be above many people's intellectual pay grades. If you're a Marvel movie fan, skip this movie. No one wants to hear your nonsense review. For the rest of you, watch this movie."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e8d3cfc3-6660-4824-a45b-0c4f725f5a06", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d7936c4060ee9e566c682e11a438d3b742f6ad0be468c1bf89f9fac8c577e951"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "krmabuska-774-770911", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-09-01", "title": null, "content": "Yorgos Lanthimos and Emma Stone's Overdone Partnership\n\nYorgos Lanthimos and Emma Stone have undeniably created some striking films together, from The Favourite to Poor Things. Their collaborations often blend sharp surrealism with Stone's fearless performances, delivering moments of brilliance that linger. But let's be honest: their relentless streak of projects is starting to feel like a one-note symphony.\n\nThe issue isn't talent-Lanthimos's offbeat vision and Stone's chameleon-like acting are still top-tier. It's the sheer frequency. Back-to-back films with the same director-actor duo can sap the freshness from even the most inventive premises. Their latest efforts, while polished, echo the same quirky, detached tone and stylized weirdness that defined their earlier work. It's like watching a brilliant chef cook the same dish repeatedly-eventually, you crave a new flavor.\n\nStone's commitment to Lanthimos's eccentric worlds is admirable, but her constant presence risks turning their films into a predictable shtick. The audience deserves variety, and both artists are versatile enough to explore beyond this partnership. A break to work with other directors or actors could reinvigorate their craft and give us something new to savor. For now, this once-exciting collaboration feels like it's overstayed its welcome, leaving a stale aftertaste."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "23d743c3-6295-4054-94e4-a4177f6eda24", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2579320c393f67130d034f1eee9a33ff068fb7255a2fa6aabc505891a64bd639"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Beyondtherain", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-10-31", "title": null, "content": "If you are a Horror Thriller fan, go see this! It has Comedy but it was too serious of a subject to make me laugh, kidnapping, torture, abuse, the movie is basically horror thriller and you can see why i say this...I did not enjoy poor things, it ended up being a Victorian Era P0RN0.... This movie is more straightforward and easier to get behind...it's a movie you must see in theaters...I went in blind, i only knew about emma stone being baId and kidnapped because this guy thinks she's an Alien...It's one of those movies you can rewatch and better than most films that have came out this year...I would compare it to the Substance, although Substance is way more wild...Go SEE THIS."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f4e4b91a-a1ba-40cc-84e9-03c3d3aad89f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "aa233f0f80e4a00b6fed71737444e87cd5347d89d28bf40fa251f04ec5495ebf"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "dorMancyx", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-10", "title": null, "content": "My hair hurts from all the head-scratching while watching Bugonia. It's like a joke that's really funny for the first few seconds, but then it keeps going and is given length, detail, drama, then plot twist - conspiracies are real and humanity is doomed. To be fair, it became quite apparent at start that the movie is a pulp fiction, hence any attempt at comprehending the story is futile because you can't make sense of a nonsense. This is not to say that the work has no worth - take Quentin - but you gotta entertain the audience in ways other than moralizing. Charisma of the actors and tension of the dialogues are what kept me going until the third act, yet my last hopes were bombarded by the total chaos of an ending featuring the absolute abandonment of logical, emotional, and storytelling principles. There's no crime in the lack of substance, the attempt to render it undeserved virtue is.\n\nI recommend if you love Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons as much as Yorgos Lanthimos."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "64824f6c-c04a-4011-bd0c-2600608c63a0", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2fa6257076ac89af466f53bfb99a787fc59e7faa02a82710fcf113ba02040a82"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "blankyblank", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-12-24", "title": null, "content": "Two men kidnap CEO, convinced she's an alien. She tries to talk her way to freedom. That's 97% of the movie without exaggeration.\n\nThe entire time you hope to get crumbs of psychology, mystery, thriller, horror, drama, thought-provoking statements, anything really but it never comes. Even the scenery is dull and uneventful since most of the movie happens in a dirty basement\n\nI've lost 2 hours and gained nothing. Don't bother. Just don't. Watch Poor Things twice if you really need Emma Stone lead in a Lanthimos movie."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7c740c19-a968-4b13-8c99-3e151286a0d3", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "fe7e37d175da9d6a0f3fd4790a61a0cad751f4e4ac2689ddf4a3d5c479c98664"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "mutate9601", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-16", "title": null, "content": "While watching Bugonia, I gradually stopped approaching it as a conventional sci-fi or conspiracy film and began reading it as a metaphor built from the film's own events and imagery. The characters at the bottom of the hierarchy are repeatedly shown performing, reacting, and suffering within a system they neither control nor fully understand-evoking the image of worker bees sustaining a larger structure.\n\nOne moment that stood out occurs when the powerful figure played by Emma Stone authorizes financial compensation for the protagonist's mother after a product-related fault. Within the film, this action is presented as responsibility or resolution, yet it feels limited. The system responds efficiently to a material or legal failure, but later, when human lives themselves are at stake, that same sense of obligation disappears. The contrast is created by the film's own progression, not external commentary.\n\nThe ending reinforces this imbalance. Emma Stone's character ultimately leaves, and the film allows the consequences for humanity to unfold without intervention. Interpreted symbolically, this resembles how, in nature, a queen bee abandons a hive when survival is no longer viable, leaving the worker bees behind. The film does not explain this choice-it simply shows it, letting the implications speak for themselves.\n\nThe repeated use of the term \"alien\" also feels deliberate. These figures are not presented as alien solely because of extraterrestrial origin, but because of how they appear and behave: visibly altered, emotionally distant, and detached from ordinary human vulnerability. Within the film's visual language, their artificiality creates a sense that they are no longer fully human. This aligns with contemporary imagery of extreme self-modification and constructed identities, though the film never states this directly-it allows the resemblance to emerge naturally.\n\nSeen this way, Bugonia does not frame humanity's collapse as the result of an external invasion, but as the outcome of distance, hierarchy, and abandonment. The film leaves viewers to sit with the discomfort rather than offering resolution.\n\nRather than delivering a clear message, Bugonia works as a reflective piece-one that invites the viewer to ask whether the system shown on screen values people as individuals, or only as long as they serve a function."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8e881fe9-e5f2-44da-88a0-505cb1f0b628", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6a1e9683c0302038d48b7c1a044458a62a532a36c39706646ec29284edd1ae94"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "John-7551", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-10-27", "title": null, "content": "Yorgos Lanthimos's Bugonia is a mesmerizing blend of absurdist satire and psychological horror, cementing his status as one of cinema's most daring auteurs. The film follows two disillusioned men who kidnap a corporate leader they believe to be an alien, but beneath its bizarre premise lies a scathing critique of paranoia, capitalism, and humanity's fragile relationship with truth. Emma Stone delivers a magnetic, layered performance, oscillating between vulnerability and menace, while Jesse Plemons brings a haunting intensity that grounds the surrealism. Lanthimos's signature offbeat tone, eerie symmetry, and deadpan humor turn each scene into both a moral puzzle and visual feast. Bugonia lingers in the mind long after the credits roll-a disturbing, darkly funny exploration of belief, control, and the madness lurking beneath modern reason."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "289189ce-1693-406f-8b39-e6ac9dc0844a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c961b2b77a5b0324330d1399cb6b833a46c3210dd63029009121c8825f6fedea"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "ChineseMurchik", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-10-11", "title": null, "content": "The movie is an adaptation of an rather obscure Korean black comedy. The source material may be considered a cult classic but seeing Begonia I feel like there was a reason it never got popular.\n\nThe film goes places well with commentary on the state of misinformation and self-victimisation plaguing our society. In what could have been a good movie about the dangers of such trends, it falls flat on its face with a ridiculous over the top ending. The adaptation is faithful but fails to exceed the original, and is an indictment on the lack of originality and creativity of the director.\n\nThe movie is carried by Emma Stone who is fantastic in her performance. Jesse Plemons plays the same character he always does - and I feel like he fails to capture the breadth of emotions required to generate sympathy for his character - which on paper should have come off a lot more sympathetic than he did on screen."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2836441f-fdaa-4537-94d5-f534f9412a79", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ce1ef8f1d79ab40da6a6c4d440ed7b85a631ea995e546568cd2a5886faf78446"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "shivg", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-05", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia (2025) This movie is pure madness - dark, strange, and oddly emotional. Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons absolutely kill it with performances that feel real and uncomfortably human. What starts like a weird sci-fi comedy slowly turns into something deeply disturbing and beautiful. The visuals are stunning, the sound design messes with your head, and the ending leaves you uneasy - like heartbreak that doesn't fully heal.\n\nThe story will feel like you know how it will go in your heart, you know how it will work but by the end, you will feel like John snow who knows nothing.\n\nNot for everyone, and that was proved in theatre with a very limited audience but definitely for those who love slow-burn chaos and emotional bruises, and madness in all. A solid 8.5 and a must watch. Lanthimos did it again."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "98c9ad86-f4d9-41f7-a3df-5b3bdec4bf2f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "14c8348576d1734f01b4d6b70fab0fb66eae6e8561bc35fe74c547f2352c20bf"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "iwatchfilmz", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-07", "title": null, "content": "Pretty much exactly what I expected.\n\nIt was a weird movie made by a guy who makes weird movies just for the sake of being weird and 2 actors (Plemons and Stone) who love taking on odd roles. I'm sure a room full of film school graduates could decode some deep political or environmental message, but for the average moviegoer it was just a strange little film.\n\nThe acting was good and the story was fascinating, but right when things were really getting interesting the movie took a hard left into ridiculousness when it could have just kept straight.\n\nI didn't like the ending. You might. I didn't.\n\nThere were other, less absurd ways to get to the final montage.\n\nI'm sure this film will get nominated for some awards because the acting was good enough to keep you engaged and the plot was just random enough to be divisive...that seems to be the bar these days.\n\nBut I don't need to see it again."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "4db0f89d-43c2-4d5a-9f05-56c3640ba2e8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "50617333a0ac4c12ec3652d41824e2539a4d9732c7e3c9a997c985e2682e9e09"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "gortx", "rating": null, "date": "2025-12-29", "title": null, "content": "Yorgos Lanthimos' remake of the 2003 crazy Korean cult film SAVE THE GREEN PLANET! Is, surprisingly for the eccentric filmmaker, actually more level-headed than the original. The basic story of a man convinced that a powerful executive is really an Alien in disguise set to destroy the Earth in seven days remains. Will Tracy's screenplay is mostly faithful to Jang Joon-hwan's original, and has plenty of bizarre turns, but, overall, it's more straightforward.\n\nThe gender switch from a male businessman in the Korean film to the high powered CEO Michelle Fuller (Emma Stone) is the most significant alteration. She is kidnapped by a floundering man soaked in conspiracy theories, Teddy (Jesse Plemons), and his docile cousin Don (Aiden Delbis). The co-captor was female in SAVE THE GREEN PLANET!. Once Fuller awakens it becomes a battle of wills between her and Teddy. She uses perfectly pitched corporate-speak to try and reason with the seemingly delusional, self-described resistance fighter. Who is the crazy one? Both?\n\nLanthimos and Tracy lay out the offbeat story in a much clearer and cogent manner than in the original. It's still as far-fetched but feels far more grounded. Stone again displays her command of the screen even while spending much of the film in shackles. Her head shaven and smeared in lotion (alien protection measures!) Stone fully commands the viewer's attention. Plemmons too, is quite good even if the character is too narrowly drawn and, frankly, not all that interesting. His cousin is sympathetic, but in a sad way. The backstory also includes a local cop who was once Teddy's babysitter (Stavros Halkias) and his mother (an unrecognizable Alicia Silverstone). Much of the film takes place at Teddy's house (complete with bee farm - look up the definition of 'Bugonia') renderings sections of it with a somewhat hangdog atmosphere. Ace Cinematographer Robbie Ryan shooting in 35mm with an appropriately boxy 1:50 aspect ratio does a fine job.. Jerskin Fendrix' moody score is atmospheric.\n\nLanthimos and Tracy's approach here pays off with a more thoughtful ending than in the original film, but Jang's high-wire go for broke gonzo energy is greatly missed. It's more than a bit surprising that Lanthimos' film could be considered conventional, but it absolutely fits. One would have expected more alterations to the material for such an original filmmaker. It is more 'logical' and it has some superior resonance in its epilogue, but it's not as fun as SAVE THE GREEN PLANET! - make of that what you will."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "26c23e9b-f304-468b-a406-45411d36d6b9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "5fbf137324e4ded7e03bfaf87e11dc9a37cdee8c8a1c1a575cea93494643b4bd"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "peggymanic", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "Review Bugonia (A remake of Jang joon-hwan's 1993 film Save the Green Planet)\n\nBugonia, the ancient erroneous belief that bees are spontaneously generated from a cow's carcass\n\nJang joon-hwan and Will Tracy successfully pen this extraordinarily entertaining film that combines brilliant dialogue with unearthly story telling. Tracy, a former writer for the Onion,(who knew?) has adapted his humor into this comedic crime drama that evolves seamlessly into a science fiction/fantasy piece.\n\nThe dialogue between Emma Stone as the kidnapped Big Pharma CEO and Jesse Plemons, her kidnapper Teddy, a downtrodden underdog who is trying to save the world, is a masterpiece in writing that addresses corporate and working class clashes amidst the ongoing destruction of earth's ecosystem. Stone's portrayal of a corporate CEO's ambitious cold rationale that fearlessly assesses her situation and aggressively attempts control only to have her powerful dialogue countered by Jesse Plemon's even more shocking crazy.\n\nAidan Delbis in his first role as someone on the autism spectrum adds depth to the story and works well as Teddy's beta sidekick Plemons and Stone deserve Oscars for their performances, which relied on the superb writing of Will Tracy and Jang.joon-hwan who simply must receive Oscars for Best Adapted Screenplay. Can't have one without the other as the writing and acting are so intertwined.\n\nAlicia Silverstone surprises as the opioid addicted mother who becomes disabled after taking part in a paid medical study with the surrealistic metaphoric imagery that efficiently communicates her story.\n\nThe strengths of the writing and acting were reinforced through Yorgos Lanthimos direction, creating this wonderfully fresh, entertaining film that thoroughly satisfies.\n\nMy only criticism is the brass band soundtrack used to create drama for contemporary desensitized audiences, stood out as a flaw within this superb work of art.\n\nBy the end of the film the audience gets that Bugonia, the ancient erroneous belief that bees are spontaneously generated from a cow's carcass, aptly captures the theme of the film where constructed corporate practices running rampant and social media have created a chaotic world where no one is on the same page and the death of mankind is a somewhat happy ending.\n\nYorgos Lanthimos Director, Jang joon-hwan and Will Tracy Writers: Jesse Plemons, Emma Stone and Aidan Delbis."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "04712959-cb6c-445c-a8a4-f74d44c9c9d3", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3cd6487bf12bc1299fa236ec80dffea60d2f3dd8fffac3deb4c70e07015bcbb3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "andrew-hill515", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-10-31", "title": null, "content": "It had all the ingredients and all the elements of a good movie but it didn't quite come together to make an actual good movie. And the ending just felt lazy, like a placeholder that never got rewritten properly.\n\nIt seemed like it had a twist and some ambiguity and maybe it's this way but maybe she's doing that, maybe she's lying now maybe she was lying before, But it threw in so many obvious twists in how things were said and presented and from the performances and the edit and direction that the last second twist was obviously going to happen from like half way through so it wasn't even slightly surprising.\n\nThen the closing montage was dumb and lazy after the lazy twist, so it was going for emotional impact but didn't produce any emotional weight whatsoever.\n\nAnd the flashbacks and black and white scenes with a voiceover like a dream sequence were we supposed to believe the theme? The event? What was said by the people in the scene or what was shown or what was said in voiceover? Some seemed to be trying to show true events but made them not true by making them dumb and wrong and dream logic and they were just inconsistent and just sucked.\n\nTLDR: Nearly good but managed not to be."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "bc66ef04-a26c-4d77-99c2-2a896055d69b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4b5f1ce4ab198f8064bf70b6ece995603af6aef0cc1945be4e4a1d0ba32706a6"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "HardyReviews_", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-16", "title": null, "content": "I must admit, I was thoroughly surprised by the ending of this film. Bugonia takes you on an intriguing and bizarre journey, as Jesse Plemons' character delves into the mysteries of mind control and extraterrestrial life. The film maintains a consistently intense atmosphere throughout, making it an engaging and thought-provoking watch. It skillfully keeps you on the edge of your seat, wondering how the plot will unfold and what unexpected twists await. The film's success lies in its ability to defy expectations, leaving me thoroughly impressed and entertained."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ef35907b-f13a-480b-b72b-b40aee41e125", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7b086f4f2056d98375d5b17a47cfdc32f48bc957936cf79efeebedff214c0a97"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Pjtaylor-96-138044", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-01", "title": null, "content": "'Bugonia (2025)' is about a pair of conspiracy theorists who kidnap a CEO in the belief she's an alien capable of negotiating a deal with her brethren to leave Earth and stop harming its residents. Shot with director Yorgos Lanthimos' signature clinical coldness but trading his films' usual monotone stiffness for a more naturalistic approach to matter-of-fact dialogue, the film balances dark comedy with crushing reality as it crafts its relatable world of heartbreaking problems and no easy solutions. It isn't really interested in answering any of the questions it asks, nor is it concerned with giving you a clear outcome - or protagonist - to root for. Despite being a three-hander, it's never clear which of the main players you're meant to be aligned with, as it's basically just a case of a bad person doing bad things to another bad person while a slightly less bad person watches with unease. There's no real thematic consistency or poignance to the picture because it doesn't really seem to say anything beyond establishing its narrative as being one which plays with recognisable concepts and emotions. It also does something that throws its underlying point into question, going so far as to perhaps undercut the point it initially makes about who's \"right\" and who's \"wrong\". Its grey mortality is part of its appeal, but its ultimate handling of it feels ever-so-slightly irresponsible if you try to sincerely connect the dots from its execution back to its conception. In the end, this is a really well-made movie that's performed to perfection and is unashamedly downbeat. It's quirky, it's uncomfortable, it's mostly entertaining. Yet, it's also slightly uneven, with a third act that's vaguely disappointing (and, even more vaguely, predictable) despite its undeniable boldness. It's definitely a good movie, but it isn't quite as emotionally gripping as I'd like it to be. I appreciate it, but I don't exactly feel it. Still, it's a solid effort that's engaging and entertaining enough to keep you happily watching for its duration. It isn't Lanthimos' best, but it isn't his worst, either."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "031b3f7a-b882-424c-bebc-76afe6b343c8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f65d581c19d325ac2d4ebfcf75c243ff91a49dc88a208813096bcfde4de6d4d5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "voodoobluesme", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-11-03", "title": null, "content": "Mix up internet conspiracy theories, corporate malfeasance, horror and some Sci Fi that makes Dr Who look sophisticated and what do you get? This unspeakable mess of a movie. The first hour was so boring I nearly left the (almost deserted) cinema. The second hour was by turns repellently violent and laughably ridiculous. If some people think Yorgos Lanthimos is the future of cinema then we're in even more trouble than I feared."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "dfb1b286-62fb-4b27-ba2b-cd0236ec3591", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e9da1029ac865787bbad5c8385b16642e1dcc66ee5b6ed16bbbf8f1423640866"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "deloudelouvain", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is exactly the movie I needed after watching two bad movies. Finally something different and interesting. The dark satirical humour made Bugonia stand out from the rest. Sci-fi and satire, it's quite a rare combination but it worked well. The story is very easy to follow and entertaining on top of that. The cast basically consists of Emma Stone, Jesse Plemons and Aidan Delbis. You have some extras but the three mentioned actors are the ones that did a great job, all very convincing. I'm not surprised by the high ratings as Bugonia will please a large audience."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "b75dbabc-8d8b-4072-9077-75a159282920", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ac7c305f7ef16bd3dc112305c988b7ce2423c831649dfe97b1504b8cce29729a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "TheVictoriousV", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-05", "title": null, "content": "While the first 8 months of 2025 weren't anything spectacular in terms of movies (unless you lived where I live and got stuff like Nickel Boys and The Brutalist during the winter and early spring), the year's festival season entailed some mighty promising titles. When I saw that the latest Yorgos Lanthimos-Emma Stone collaboration had scored 100% on Rotten Tomatoes and even won over certain Lanthimos nay-sayers after its Venice premiere, I knew we were gonna eat good this autumn. (This is to say nothing of the buzz around One Battle After Another, as well as Park Chan-wook, Chloe Zhao, et al., but more on them another time.)\n\nBased on Jang Joon-hwan's Save the Green Planet, Bugonia is the tale of two conspiracy theorists -- or rather, one conspiracy theorist and his less-than-adroit cousin -- kidnapping a Big Pharma CEO whom they believe is an Andromedan extraterrestrial, complicit in a grand master plot to mess up the ecosystem, make humans into obsequious drones, conquer us via division, and whatever else is secretly going on behind the scenes of our shared bedlam. They believe she can be persuaded, or forced, to contact the Mothership and get the Andromedans to leave us be.\n\nThis is a marvelous film, and further rumination and a rewatch may force me to conclude it's the best work of both Lanthimos and Stone's careers. I know I say this almost every time there is a new Emma Stone film -- especially one where she works with Lanthimos -- but she truly is at that level.\n\nJesse Plemons is also superb, which is once again expected, but there is something truly special about how he here captures the incorrigibility and main character syndrome of conspiracy theorists (who have only gotten worse with time; the film partly examines why), as well as the way they snap during conversations when they realize the sheer irremdiable wrongness of the narrative they've made their raison d'\u00eatre. The big \"find\", to use Brandon Streussnig's phrasing, is Aidan Delbis, who knocks it out of the park as the slow-witted cousin.\n\nI can admit a few issues with the film; more negative reviews posit that its social commentary -- its satire of girlboss feminism, late-stage capitalism, political labels, the yearning for purpose, and just humanity's trajectory in general -- occasionally sounds a bit obvious and shallow. It doesn't have the Poor Things excuse of filtering everything through an infant-brained Frankenstein-ian creature, but I do think the comments that people are referring to (some of them, at least) work well enough for the context in which we hear them: which characters speak the dialogue and what exactly they're attempting to convey to each other.\n\nLike Poor Things, Bugonia has of course also come under fire from the \"depiction v endorsement\" understanders, who think Lanthimos gets a kick out of putting women through Hell in his movies. This is not (and has never been) anything more than a 2020s sequel to Roger Ebert's pearl-clutching about women in the films of David Lynch. (I'm sure Emma Stone -- the film's co-producer, by the way -- is just as aghast to be forced to work with Lanthimos as Dern, Lee, Watts, and Rossellini were with Lynch.) And while I can understand why critics find it weird that Lanthimos changed the torture-and-kidnapping victim from male to female, is it not also weird that y'all more clearly understand that the torture is bad when it's happening to a male character (Save the Green Planet) than to a female one (Bugonia), in which case you need someone to look into the camera and clarify it to us (read: you)?\n\nI will also say this (if we must speak about the potentially harmful impact of Bugonia): There is a good chance IRL conspiracy theorists will be humored by this picture -- yes, in spite of the fact that they are being critiqued.\n\nI mentioned before that the portrayal is strikingly accurate, and I very much speak from first-hand experience (I have even done exactly what Stone's character does, being forced to correct their grammar but then joking about how speaking correctly must surely also be part of the grand master plot to \"indoctrinate\" us through education). I am thus painfully aware that they think films like this prove them right, not DESPITE satirizing them, but because of it: the movie exists specifically as an NWO-mandated countermeasure to make them look silly, on top of signaling what's next in the reptilian scheme, because confession protects them from bad karma or something. (Even the depiction of Flat Earth, which initially looks to be floating in space, which more and more tinfoilers don't even believe exists, turned out to be -- essentially -- accurate to how they think our realm functions.)\n\nBut then, on the other hand, conspiracy theorists may feel that parts of the movie \"get to the bottom\" of them -- the theorists, I mean -- to such an uncomfortable degree that they might not run with it. It isn't wholly accurate to say that the text mocks these people wholesale. There may be jokes at their expense, but it does endeavour to understand where this brand of working-class wreck comes from, and why so many have gone down this path in recent years.\n\nDunning-Kruger narcissism (wanting to be smarter than experts, and those damned \"normies\" who blindly agree with facts) and lockdown-induced brain rot only explain some of it, as I noted in my 2023 Conspiracy Guide parody. But Bugonia acknowledges the desperation that lower-class folks find themselves in, in this age of illness, death, and ever-so-hopeless visions of the future; the desperation to sense that there's some great master plan that ties everything together so that reality makes a lot more sense than it actually does. In a sense, though, something does indeed tie it all together: late capitalist society -- a world where everyone has nothing, and more and more is taken from them -- created many of these wretches.\n\nAnywho, what else did I like? Well, as is par for the Lanthimos course, there is plenty of personality to the cinematography and editing; the black-and-white flashback sequences have a particular pulsating rhythm to them. Then there's Jerskin Fendrix's awesome music, which sounds a bit like if John Williams' Star Wars score went to Hell and came back again.\n\nIt is true that I am a sucker for movies with this particular view of humanity -- and the future we may all be headed towards, however much we cling to this or that ideology/deity/\"explanation\" as doom nonchalantly creeps ever closer. But I think most of the objections to Bugonia are fairly meaningless (and can be excused by its status as a comedic satire) and that you should all watch it. As Streussnig's review also notes, you might even discover a certain emotional resonance to it that makes it stand out from Lanthimos' other, supposedly \"just plain kooky\" works.\n\nA friend wrote that you might like the film more if you dislike Lanthimos (supposing you're not one of the aforementioned \"nothing bad must ever happen to lady characters\" bloggers). As far as I'm concerned, however, he's done it again!\n\nI am beyond glad this man gets the freedom he does in Hollywood. Maybe, as much as the Andromedans would disagree, there is some hope for us all. Oh, and before I forget: Yes, Stavvys' gut looks exactly as epic on the big screen as you've heard."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3416c2e5-a674-453b-896a-885c4cd81027", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e63f70d7d3f0c1f3b4e7d4bb24a930ee0bd0ecec6d672c812404bf08ecd1d99d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "migueldbmiranda", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-02", "title": null, "content": "I think they who made the movie was very confused about the movie story.\n\nWe have a begining about conspiracy abd then about mental issues caused by life bad events and at the end the whole story is destroyed and become a non sense parade.\n\nMy rating would be much better without the worst ending ever."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7b001bae-10d1-4f18-9887-fe841bac2f6d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.186435", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6e4f796701b7848bb4d962654e6b689dd70059f180166fdd98f0fb8beffdcf27"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "MaximusQ8", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-04", "title": null, "content": "This cinematic masterpiece boldly blends multiple genres, including dark comedy, science fiction, thriller, and horror.\n\n\n* From the mad Greek director Yorgos Lanthimos, this masterpiece tells the story of Teddy, a conspiracy theorist who kidnaps Michelle Fuller, the CEO of a giant pharmaceutical company. He is convinced she is an Andromedan alien bent on destroying Earth.\n\n\n\n* Despite its crime and kidnapping premise, the film transcends mere suspense and thrills, becoming at its core a meditation on human nature, the madness of belief, the fear of the other, and collective moral guilt. Before delving further, let's briefly touch upon the origin of the idea and the meaning of the title. The concept is borrowed from the 2003 South Korean film \"Save the Green Planet\" (a pinnacle of South Korean cinematic creativity). However, instead of mere imitation or literal replication, the director and his team have created a new blend, one that is darker, more metaphorical in its depiction of reality, and even more terrifying from a psychological and social perspective.\n\n\nThe \"transformation\" here is profound, granting the film a powerful independence for artistic and philosophical reconstruction. I'm not saying the Korean film is \"superficial\" or \"lacking in depth\"-quite the opposite-but this new treatment is deeper and darker.\n\nHere, it avoids the trap of literal adaptation, opting instead for a radical reinterpretation that applies the original story to today's world. A world burdened by conspiracy theories, a collapse of trust, and an environmental anxiety that pervades contemporary consciousness.\n\nAs for the title \"Bugonia,\" it's not a random word; it also carries a very deep symbolic meaning, linked to ancient myths and the film's narrative. This word is derived from the Greek/Roman myth of \"Bugonia,\" a ritual believed in ancient times to create bees from the carcass of a dead bull.\n\nThe Greek word \"Bous\" means bull.\n\nThe word \"Gonia\" means birth or emergence.\n\nTherefore, the title literally means: \"The Birth of Bees from the Bull\" or \"The Birth of Life from Death.\"\n\nThe ancients believed that bees spontaneously arose from the decay of flesh, meaning that life was born from decomposition.\n\nAccordingly, the choice of title was not arbitrary or a case of \"controversy for the sake of controversy.\" Not at all! Rather, it carries connotations that perfectly align with the film's theme: life born from ruin and chaos, just as the \"bee\" is born from the bull's carcass in the myth. The film attempts to ask us:\n\nIs it possible for meaning to emerge from the chaos of violence?\n\nOr can something of value be born from madness and collapse?\n\nHowever, the film casts doubt on the answer to this question and offers a bleak one.\n\nThe bees in the film are a powerful symbol of the disruption of nature and the insidious intervention of pharmaceutical companies, which are corrupting the modern world for profit, not for public health, as they claim.\n\nThe death of the bees signifies the death of the ecosystem, and thus serves as a metaphor for the demise of humanity, a central theme in the events. In the myth, the death of the bull is a prerequisite for the birth of the bees.\n\nI've lingered too long on this point!\n\nGenerally, the legend of \"Bogonia\" is based simply on a \"scientific myth\" that states people tried to understand nature, so they invented a false story to reassure themselves.\n\nBack to the main topic, the film... Actor Jesse Plemons delivered a complex performance as Teddy. He's not just an extremist, but also psychologically wounded, driven by intense emotion and madness. In my opinion, this is an exceptional performance for him and the strongest of his entire career.\n\nAs for actress Emma Stone, she played Michelle brilliantly. Although her character might seem harsh, she appeared as a strange being-you can't tell if she's a machine or an alien-but she possesses contradictory layers of strength, fear, coldness, and perhaps a hidden humanity. This made the interaction between the two characters intense and emotionally charged.\n\nAs usual, the director didn't allow for any relaxation. This masterpiece felt like a \"visual nightmare,\" with camera angles that suffocate the characters, dim lighting, and garish colors, all contributing to a sense of psychological terror and isolation.\n\nThe soundtrack and dramatic pacing added a dimension of constant tension and apprehension, making the viewer feel uneasy in a way that reflects the characters' state.\n\nThe film doesn't just tell a story of kidnapping or the thrills that follow; it becomes a mirror to our era, addressing conspiracy theories, isolation, loss of trust, environmental panic, and manipulation by pharmaceutical companies, making its voice a resounding \"shock\" in the context of the modern world.\n\nIt also discusses the concept of \"faith\"-not necessarily in a religious sense-but faith as a compensation for emptiness, pain, and betrayal. It explores how the human mind can transform into a belief system, even one based on superstition, simply to find meaning or soothe its fear of reality.\n\n\n* The film isn't for everyone, as it focuses heavily on symbolism, mythology, psychological religion, and conspiracy. If you're watching it superficially or merely for entertainment, don't watch it; it won't be suitable for you. Its weighty ideas are difficult to digest. In other words, it's not for visual enjoyment (the eye) but for intellectual stimulation (the mind), and some may feel confused or even disturbed despite all this.\n\n\n\n* It freely reflects the fragility of humanity when trust in society, institutions, or even moral principles is shattered. This is when anxieties, fears, and conspiracy theories emerge as a pathetic psychological defense.\n\n\n\n* It's a frank and bold critique of capitalism and the large pharmaceutical companies (represented by \"Michelle\" and \"The Corporation\"). This character is not just an individual, but a symbol of a blind economic structure that shapes human destinies, whether people believe in it or fight against it. Its impact is on the environment (like the death of bees) and on people (pain, illness, deception). The film connects the destruction of the natural environment with human exploitation, making \"bees\" a symbol of the natural world being demolished, like a building torn down from its highest point to its foundation. - His message is a meditation on collective madness. How can ideas that seem \"familiar\" or \"widespread\" in the information age transform into deadly beliefs, where superstition becomes fact, and anyone who disagrees with you becomes an enemy?\n\n\nBefore concluding, this film invites reflection, not only on who is the criminal or who is at fault, but also on the structure that created this division, this fear, this psychological violence. It is a question about humanity in an age of isolation, globalization, media manipulation, and environmental degradation, not to mention the \"deliberate\" misinformation disseminated by media outlets that some consider trustworthy. With exceptional acting and a daring direction that doesn't shy away from challenging the audience, the flat-Earth map, which I believe in, reappears repeatedly.\n\nIn conclusion, Yorgos Lonthimos. Here, he doesn't offer answers, but rather lays bare a nightmare before you. However, he achieves this with captivating cinematic beauty, powerful acting, and audacious presentation. Therefore, \"Bogonia\" is not a film for everyone. But it is certainly a film worth watching, thinking about, and perhaps rewatching to illuminate some of its darker corners further."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "b08c03be-2e52-4bca-b393-9b407f20aca2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6d7df6ea2be389a20d304eec7bdb054134803976112ba2a31c89ab43f27463d6"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Borracho_Porrero", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-09-04", "title": null, "content": "While i was initially intrigued that someone from the west decided to tackle 2003\"s Save The Green Planet, and realizing enough time had passed since its release that an entire generation is most likely oblivious to it. I was definitely going to give it a watch, being a big big fan of the original. The film is about an alien posing as a large tech CEO and the humans that hope to expose her to the world at large. It combines the suspense, psychological thriller, horror, and dark comedy genres(the original also had romance)but that was apparently nixed in this new interpretation. The aesthetic was dark and believable, i will confess to being unfamiliar with this director but he seems to have a particular style that hes after but it just didnt have the same impact on me as the original film. Im not sure if its because the special twisty ending already been revealed but i just couldnt take the main protagonist serious in this version and i felt like even if i hadnt seen STGP that it would have been one of those endings that almost felt predictable because they were trying so hard to make you focus on one aspect that it had to be a red herring, whereas Planet completely blindsided me with the ending. For sure it was not an easy film to remake by any stretch of the imagination. This is a very serviceable attempt, just not a really great one like its predecessor imo."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "27645cbb-c7df-49ab-8a13-38aa6fee4544", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3f9c5d70d7fd80092c2424292092681b17a9979f39c768e49c2da1de65ce2b93"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "JulienM-116", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-12-31", "title": null, "content": "This movie does almost everything right for me. The acting is excellent, the plot is engaging, and the message behind the story is genuinely meaningful. What stands out most is how open the film is to interpretation. Viewers can think about its themes in different ways, but at the same time, it works just as well if you are simply looking to be entertained. The story itself is exciting and unpredictable, taking the audience on a wild ride, even if it starts a bit slowly. Overall, it is a fantastic film and one I would strongly recommend."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "20c463ec-52af-49e9-84c1-6d3c6779f170", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "ca949ca4fbfcced7696c93d2b9d97589689c8a83bbabdab6206d6ac2115f916a"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "TheFilmDetective", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-01", "title": null, "content": "This was an interesting movie it's not bad, but definitely not amazing just an average watch,it's got potential but the pacing of the storyline was mediocre and felt very slow at times, making it hard to stay fully immersed in the movie it had its moments were a few funny scenes that actually landed well and broke up the tension nicely but this film also had alot of direction from the movie poor things 2023 which personally I didn't think was anything special What really became bizarre and really confusing was one specific scene I didn't see coming at all it genuinely shocked me in the best way possible because I wasn't expecting it at all.\n\nAs for the movie ending, it was a more on the comedic / goofy presence which didn't totally fit the tone of the rest of the movie but was at least a little bit of entertainment."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "00c35484-fa97-4c8b-8ad8-27ac35d1bff9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "69291632e68879db17485dcdba0d05f7356b6279cfef592fda882f5a7f67e7ca"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Vagid_Gasanov", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-21", "title": null, "content": "Let me start with a few words about the director. Yorgos Lanthimos became my personal discovery of 2025. I can't say he's joined the ranks of my favorite directors or that his films are always masterpieces for me, but at the very least each of his works is something unique. His distinctive, slightly absurd approach and the way he turns schizophrenic ideas into a coherent, engaging product make me look forward to each new film he creates.\n\nI've already seen three of his movies, and not a single one has disappointed me.\n\nAs for Bugonia, the absurdity began right from the start. My girlfriend almost immediately said, \"Where did you take me?\" To which I replied that this was probably his most \"normal\" film among the ones we've seen. And indeed, that did seem to be the case for the first two thirds.\n\nAlthough the ending is practically predictable from the very beginning (at least based on who's directing and which genres are listed), you still gladly fall for the trick and play by the rules the author sets.\n\nThe plot follows two not-quite-sane brothers who kidnap a successful businesswoman, convinced that she is an alien. The absurdity of their actions, coupled with the acting, creates plenty of comedic moments. Yet nothing that happens is actually \"funny\" - the situation is terrifyingly disturbing, and you can't tell whether it's a comedy or a thriller.\n\nFor me, the film was engaging from start to finish, not giving me a chance to get bored for even a minute. At the same time, it touches on both personal and fairly global themes. The ending, in the director's trademark style, clearly won't appeal to everyone (my girlfriend, for example, wished it had ended a little earlier - and I get her). But the film definitely won't leave anyone indifferent.\n\nIn the end, I want to highlight the traditionally expressive visuals, the interesting cinematography, and the fantastic performances by Jesse Plemons and Emma Stone - a few of her reactions and unexpected facial \"attacks\" made us laugh out loud.\n\nFinal score: 7.5/10\n\nPros: \n* Satirical, absurdist humor\n* Acting\n* Visuals\n* The pacing almost never drags\n\n\nCons: \n* Predictability\n* A divisive ending (for some)\n\n\nOverall, it turned out to be a solid piece of sharp social satire that doesn't let you get bored, but also doesn't say anything radically new. Not a masterpiece, but definitely the kind of film you want to discuss right after watching it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a6de243d-2d6d-45fc-9d8d-83a9fc6a22ea", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f816837cd034f3df12ed88ca483e8bc9cb37547e3ab470e337193ed9723e6a56"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "deborahcwendt", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-08", "title": null, "content": "I enjoyed the movie until toward the end. I think most people guessed fairly early on what the end result was going to be. The final scenes were kind of a let down, a little crude and the costumes left a lot to be desired (Michelin man look). All the actors did a great job and I am now curious to see \"Save the Green Planet.\""}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8ea2bafa-35d9-465e-94ba-0972f24481a8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c7852f36331b3a88687f0c23cc6eb532699380136b65fd8b50a196eb8bd04ffa"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "ngoutzoulias", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-11-09", "title": null, "content": "This is the first time in my life that I have gone to the trouble of writing a movie review. No plot whatsoever, we had to sit through 2 hours of waiting for something meaningful to happen. Extremely slow, a couple of scenes that captivated you only because they were extremely disturbing, and really nothing to look forward to throughout the movie. I respect people liking it, it's just not for me."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0756b659-1cc4-4b44-a26f-e144440445b2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "011f427051b330f113570f04f4a2274e5d0a5851ef1007120d77efaade84f807"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "c_c_getty", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-29", "title": null, "content": "What a wild ride and highly entertaining film this was. Yorgos Lanthimos latest film hits on many controversial topics including Conspiracy Theories, Aliens, Autism, Mental Illness and even Sexual Assault. Plus you could even toss in a little apocalyptic theory and corporate overreach as well. Yet somehow, I found myself chuckling uncomfortably throughout, that's how well written Bugonia is. Jesse Plemons, Emma Stone and new comer Aidan Delbis keep you glued to screen as you wonder just WTF is going to happen next.\n\nI actually had a hard time figuring out who are we supposed to like or dislike in this film, as Plemon's and Stone's characters make you flip flop between emotions a few times as the plot thickens. But that was something I really enjoyed as well.\n\nNo spoilers here, but I was able to figure out how the film was going to end just before the halfway point, and still my attention never wavered.\n\nWell worth the 2 hours of engagement, I'd score this one an 8/10, and it's very likely I'll be watching it again. Can't wait to see what Lanthimos has up his sleeve for us next."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "2e8637de-80a0-42eb-ad3b-32e89a64cbe8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3591fc0ed24884b9c092b1ec8b656738f5ba946aabbe2cac1de886590948b84f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "bnastali", "rating": 10, "date": "2026-01-03", "title": null, "content": "Love thought-provoking film? Here is a bloody gem that just keeps getting better as the minutes roll on to greater madness and pending violence. Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons push things to epic craziness and the use of wildly off-kilter symphonic music lights the way to machine gun-like power. Watch this and start 2026 with a very loud and viseral bang."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e2498231-55cf-4f39-958e-1c2036d53a00", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6e3a8835cf0ff7f133a3a2741b1e5f1acd53cab3fad97eb71c47520d2cad6e99"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "JaredPono", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-10-27", "title": null, "content": "Emma Stone is undeniably fantastic in this, as she always is, and Plemmons puts on a great performance as well. However, there is not much else good I can say about this movie. It is not nearly as good or as smart as I wanted it to be, and I struggle to understand how a movie that takes place in a basement for 90% of the movie's runtime cost upwards of 50 million dollars. The ending was expected, but didn't really feel deserved either. I dont think this film particularly said anything worthwhile and wasnt crazy enough to be a beginning to end joyride. I love Yorgos, but this is my least favorite project from him so far."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "f2f6eb0c-9d22-4854-a1fe-d5d48ecfd3ec", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1edce89fd86507662c3a2cf91718d4c3414289ecd07ff537d28f51aa5338f2a1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "gpeck-60598", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-16", "title": null, "content": "Teddy's mission was to meet with the ruler of the andromedas and convince her that humans were worth saving. But because of what she saw in him first hand, she knew that humans were not worth saving. He had the \"truth\" yet this truth only blinded him from an even deeper and more complicated truth\n\nTeddy wanted to be the one to save the human race - yet he ended up being the one to destroy the human race."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "80f99205-d037-4be8-b4f0-65c572702672", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "84ec50c3a355b767676c2e68a70fffe01d0117b486fe9d364fae4a71d860a63e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "QuintenC-53", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-09", "title": null, "content": "The first half of the movie is objectively quite good. There's a lot that it does well in terms of building suspense, making you hate certain characters and love others (sometimes even simultaneously), and it puts the characters in increasingly high stakes situations that delve into intrigue. Personally, the humor wasn't for me, but there were a few chuckles it got out of me, and the theater seemed to appreciate it a lot more than I did, so it's clearly doing something right. I also though it explored the dynamic of captivity in a very interesting way, and it was also interesting to see how each character was held captive to their own delusions (Ted to his anti-intellectualism, Don to his love for his abusive family, and Michelle to her habit of passive-aggressively treating others as subhuman) For that, this is the lowest score I could possibly give it in good faith, because there is just so much that it does well\n\nI say that because the ending is a huge miss. HUGE spoiler warning ahead\n\nThe movie is about a character who has a firm belief that aliens have held control over the Earth, and are the source of all of humanity's problems. This is obviously portrayed as delusional, and a large part of the movie is the protagonist trying to break down that delusion to plot her escape\n\nHowever, the movie ends with her using a teleporter to return to her mothership, and hold a meeting with the alien council on whether or not she should end the human race\n\nTo me, this was such a departure from the original premise of the film, it felt like it came out of nowhere, and recontectualized the film in a way that made it feel like it was no longer interesting. It almost feels like something a sitcom would do for a movie in-universe as a way to make fun of weird movie tropes.\n\nI feel like if I were to watch this movie again knowing that this was the case the whole time, almost all of the stakes would be gone, and this movie would feel almost, if not entirely pointless\n\nTL;DR, The movie is objectively good, even if it's a little slow at first, but the ending is such a departure from the rest of the movie that it really took me out of it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5ef12a58-d824-4037-a3c7-f3bc5e141505", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "e921d6f8d217a04e41181b48095abef8bb63f983b0d336099968fe52d1f161a2"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "fachriyousa14", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia appears absurd, provocative, and terrifying at the same time. The film's theme, which pokes at every detail of conspiracy theory obsession as well as criticism of corporations and the environment, successfully gives us a rather thought-provoking question: who do we trust? And who do we believe in this already \"crazy\" era. Its script also cleverly manages to mix various genres - satire, sci-fi, psychological, and horror - all of which work well and successfully deliver a very interesting absurd atmosphere. Bugonia's strength is also enhanced by the extraordinary performances of Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons. Stone appears smart, captivating, terrifying, and intimidating - I'm not surprised if she receives her 5th Oscar nomination next year. Plemons is no less incredible; sometimes he makes us annoyed but often makes us pity him thanks to his fragile performance.\n\nBugonia succeeds in becoming one of the best films of 2025, the most accessible work from Yorgos Lanthimos but also one of the best from the director."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d16fe0ee-014b-40bf-9b6c-d24a45f73486", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "866b40b7d65e53eabd3102e995983ae3505fc685000f205bdabfe2257b2ddc49"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "mike_bike_kite", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-06", "title": null, "content": "I found every part of this film excellent apart from the ending. The acting, cinematography and story line were all great. As a psychological thriller it was great and I'd easily of given it 8/10 but as a SciFi film it lacked something. I'll quickly say that I enjoy SciFi films but, to me, it simply felt like something had been bolted onto the film that was completely unnecessary."}}
