{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e0036ffd-319e-4d8d-9cec-11244e7e451a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "2ba477c250b70245ea2412819350ccea3383966bc8717d33788abeac4917cc58"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "hunterhastings-18638", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-06", "title": null, "content": "Teddy what the heck are you doing! He was so on to that Alien it was awesome. He had her pegged from the beginning, then just totally lost it at the end and she was running circles around him. Poor guy! Speaking of poor guy, Don, I felt so bad for him and to go out like he did was terrible.\n\nI liked this movie. Totally recommended it to a friend. Just wish Teddy and Don could've made it to the mothership."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cb9c20f9-37cf-4c70-9dc7-de928f963484", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "83df19d3297154cd199f8138d0777c3fc220a537871d5e5f8252c222a3a0c90b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "nzmmrpxp", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-11-03", "title": null, "content": "If Bugonia proves anything, it's that Yorgos Lanthimos has officially run out of strange things to say and is now just throwing bees, metaphors, and random absurdities at the screen hoping someone will call it genius. Spoiler: it's not.\n\nThe film buzzes with self-importance but delivers nothing but confusion and eye-rolls. It's like watching a two-hour perfume commercial directed by someone who hates storytelling. Every frame screams, \"Look how artistic I am!\" while the audience quietly wonders if they should just check their phone.\n\nThe performances are flat, the dialogue sounds like it was written by ChatGPT in nightmare mode, and the plot-if you can even call it that-flies around aimlessly before collapsing under the weight of its own symbolism.\n\nBy the time the credits roll, you're left feeling not enlightened, not provoked, but simply exhausted. Bugonia isn't bold, it's bloated. It's not thought-provoking, it's thought-exhausting."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "791ac62b-9be6-4a3b-887d-7306d6482c56", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a655966905fa6fa2d98d6bc464771a9226cbc26c5f406d4a620a3b37cbf502a9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "evanston_dad", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-18", "title": null, "content": "Yorgos Lanthimos's latest wackout dives into conspiracy theorists and the women they take hostage.\n\nJesse Plemons, Emma Stone, and Aidan Delbis are giving three of the best performances of the year in this mixed bag of a movie. Lanthimos films are so weird that the actors have to nail the material in order for it to work, and these three do.\n\nWhat I liked about \"Bugonia\" is that it explores why manufactured narratives are so popular in our world right now, and that the people who buy into them are seeking a sense of control and rationale that the random universe is just not going to give them. What I didn't like about \"Bugonia,\" in a late plot twist that almost made me hate the movie for a moment, is that the conspiracy theorist ends up being right. I know it's meant to be a provocative joke on the part of Lanthimos, but I don't like anything that validates the lunacy invading people's minds right now in the real world. And though I thought the final moments of the movie, set memorably to a version of \"Where Have All the Flowers Gone,\" were compelling and left me with an overall good impression of the film, they were also unbearably bleak. I may have my moments when I feel like the human race is a failed experiment that should be put out of its misery, but I can't let that be my predominant mindset or I'd never get out of bed in the morning.\n\nOne thing this movie brought home to me that I've never thought much about is the sadness that motivates conspiracy theorists. We're used to seeing them as crazy, frequently aggressive people who are shouting on social media and stirring up trouble. But when I step back and think about the level of fear and desperation it would take to make someone believe something that's obviously insane because it's preferable to the reality they're actually living, the sadness almost takes my breath away.\n\nIn the world of Yorgos Lanthimos I rate \"Bugonia\" below films like \"Dogtooth\" and \"The Favourite\" but above films like \"The Lobster\" and \"The Killing of a Sacred Deer.\"\n\nGrade: A-"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9361596f-8bf3-48d1-a734-19813341100e", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "4be7495677e799c57e380396965b1c6168541e78a6d5a17dc10acb1fc4ed7776"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "neil-476", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-09", "title": null, "content": "Michelle, CEO of a pharmaceutical corporation, is kidnapped by conspiracy theorist Teddy and his cognitively disadvantaged cousin Don. Believing her to be an Andromedan intent in subjugating/destroying the human race (and wiping out the bees), they shave her head (to prevent her from communicating with the mothership) and pressure her into getting them to that ship to negotiate with the Andromedan Emperor at the lunar eclipse in four days' time. Further complicated by Teddy's feelings about his mother being in a coma due to medications from Michelle's company, the situation has her using all her skills to try to negotiate with the paranoid and unstable Teddy, ranging from trying to use the muscle of her position to going along with his fantasy. Meanwhile, Teddy is prepared to use torture to get his way. And the film creates a constant niggle \"What if Teddy's right?\"\n\nBilled as a science fiction black comedy, I didn't find this film really qualified as either. It is, however, after a slow start, a tense paranoia suspense thriller. It is well-scripted (with reservations about aspects of the narrative of the final act), with superb performances from Emma Stone and, especially, Jesse Plemons as Jesse. There's a lot of social commentary, and Jorgos Lanthimos brings a great deal of his quirky vision to it.\n\nBe prepared for some explicit violence. Not much of it, but sudden and shocking.\n\nIncidentally, I see \"another masterpiece from Lanthimos\", a sentiment which always results in me going \"Uh oh\" when I see it applied to Tarantino, Aronofsky, the Coens, Snyder, Peele etc. - talented filmmakers but with over-effusive fanbases. Lanthimos has produced a film here which is unique, with laudable qualities, but it's not a masterpiece."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d2579d43-b2fb-429b-b134-7b181a4cea34", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c7381945caa6c8c11d092bfed6e75844255f6e8a31c66ec8a91e1a98d1c90252"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "mariiamonya", "rating": 7, "date": "2026-01-21", "title": null, "content": "It was confusing, interesting, at times boring, weird and many other adjectives that I still can't put together in my head after watching this masterpiece. I've never watched films by this director before (thank goodness) and it's not usually the genre that interests me very much, but this film made a very strong impression on me. I'm unlikely to watch it again, because it was difficult to watch even once. Also, to understand the essence, I had to watch the explanations, but the thoughts about this film will remain in my head for a long time."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3cf6c10a-3bb1-4ef0-8038-707ca4ba8c8f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a99169fdecdc0ef9812189455351897203b96ebf3ec5a5ba6a75a3190645c892"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "ferguson-6", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-05", "title": null, "content": "Greetings again from the darkness. We can only assume there were conspiracy theorists during the time of cavemen since alarmists have existed at every other stage of humanity. It's intriguing to assume there is more going on 'behind the curtain' than what we see with our own eyes. We feel there must be a reason those other people get rich or escape the judicial system or hold onto power ... while we are stuck in the role of being just everyday folks. Filmmaker Yorgos Lanthimos has a track record of unconventional projects (POOR THINGS, 2023; THE FAVOURITE, 2018; THE LOBSTER, 2015), and this time, he and screenwriter Will Tracy (THE MENU, 2022) have remade the 2013 award-winning South Korean cult film, SAVE THE GREEN PLANET!, by Jang Joon-hwan ... and it's a doozy.\n\nTeddy (Jesse Plemons) is a radicalized beekeeper whose conspiracy theories have been built through specific podcasts and online extremists. He has dragged his well-meaning cousin Don (the film debut of neurodivergent actor Aidan Delbis) so far into these beliefs that they have both chemically castrated in order to remain focused. That focus is on Michelle Fuller (two-time Oscar winner Emma Stone), a high-powered Biomedical CEO, whom the men are convinced is the Earth-based leader and mastermind of the aliens committed to destroying mankind.\n\nAdding to this is the distinct contrast between these two factions. Teddy and Don are a grungy, unkempt duo living in a dilapidated house, while Michelle is an impeccably dressed, confident woman living and working in a pristine home and office. A less-than-smooth kidnapping occurs as the men wear jumpsuits and masks that are worth a chuckle. Once Michelle is chained to the cot in their basement, her head is shaved (for real) and antihistamine cream is spread over her body. Teddy believes she communicates with her home base through her hair, and that the cream will numb her powers against them.\n\nThis is as bonkers as it sounds, yet it's actually very intense and leads to some elevated verbal sparring between Teddy the believer and Michelle the polished executive. Corporate greed, big pharma, and the destruction of bees are all topics of discussion, and these conversations are key to the story. See, it's only three days to the next lunar eclipse and Teddy is convinced that's the only window for negotiations with Michelle's alien community.\n\nStavros Halkias as the local sheriff and Teddy's former babysitter, and Alicia Silverstone as Teddy's mother have key supporting roles. Production Designer James Price creates the contrast required for the story, and composer Jerskin Fendrix fits the mood for each scene. Whether you figure out the twist early or not, it's still worthy of discussion on whether aliens are a bigger threat to our planet than ourselves."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9ef44532-bee7-4a2c-a07c-b9b21ce302be", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "60925ea483106cc8174307a437494bd64664c693d63e575bb070b564d22eabc8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Jeremy_Urquhart", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-11-13", "title": null, "content": "Lanthimos burned me with Kinds of Kindness, which I still kind of dislike because of how self-indulgent and patience-testing it was, but Bugonia is a step in the right direction again. Or it might be that I just prefer Yorgos Lanthimos when he's working with more sci-fi, fantastical, or horror elements, because I think The Lobster and Poor Things are easily his best, with Bugonia and Killing of a Sacred Deer being mid-tier. The others, I can do without really.\n\nBugonia's a bit slow, but once it starts taking some more risks, I felt it won me over again. Even before it gets more interesting, I think Emma Stone and (especially) Jesse Plemons are both very good, but I do wonder whether Lanthimos might have to take a break from his Favourites for a bit in the future.\n\nThere were still some small things here that were a bit irritating, other than the pacing. Lots of the shots are a bit boring, but then there are other times when the static camerawork and long takes work (any monologue, basically, plus an amazingly well-staged shot with tons of stuff happening in the foreground and background near the end of the film). Also, talking about the most striking images here would involve going into discussion of the ending, and I feel that's better not to do, since the final act really elevates the whole thing in my eyes."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d2b5db0e-8687-45b2-9c4b-bc358a431a70", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "987ae2e0aecdbab41fe754c755cd2f0d5877fb815c2eba5b456ab3960bc808e3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "kutola", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-20", "title": null, "content": "I would rewatch this movie for wonderful acting and details of environment for sure. For me it was not a movie I pondered on afterwards, but watching it was definitely a time well spent.\n\nAnd also, I haven't seen all the movies by Yorgos Lanthimos, but this one was the \"lightest\"/\"most digestible\" so far."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7f1759c4-73db-46fc-afe7-ba7037cc96a2", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "32ee0fd30d57d61d29b4762c46a156dfc59b6e11e233aead1311a9aec0e2f903"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "gfrancis0", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-01", "title": null, "content": "I think it is tricky to write this review without spoilers, but I'll give it a shot. I enjoy a movie where you do not really know what is happening next or what is true and what is not, but the movie needs to explain at least the basics somewhere along the way, which this movie certainly does. If an original movie with some twists and turns appeals to you, I would recommend you avoid reading any spoilers before watching Bugonia. The acting is great, the sets and costumes resonate as authentic, for the most part. It is obvious that the writer of this movie has no idea what it is like to be a CEO of a company, but that is a minor concern. I will also say that the ending is somewhat disappointing, I would describe it as both phoned in and also drawn out, maybe you can figure out what I mean when you watch it. I enjoyed it enough to recommend it, my wife thought it was too strange for her."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "176b67b5-7544-4e93-8765-8741e862224a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f3b07729ac097910f0999404f22248619a91202a1098c70c85eb9654fad837c6"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "fabiolpinheiro1993", "rating": 10, "date": "2025-10-28", "title": null, "content": "Yorgos Lanthimos proves once again why he's one of the best filmmakers working today - and one of my personal favorites. He's always pushing boundaries, showing that there are no limits to creativity or boldness. His films are everything cinema should be: a wild, unforgettable ride that takes you to places you never expect.\n\nWhile I wasn't the biggest fan of his last film, we're back on track here with another genius, brilliant, completely bonkers, and impossible-to-predict masterpiece. Yes, it's a remake - a first for him - but it's still unmistakably his, and it feels like it was always meant to be.\n\nIt's a deceptively simple yet utterly insane premise that pulls you in like a magnet and never lets go, even during the quietest moments. There's always more bubbling beneath the surface. The film overflows with dark humor, unexpected twists, gorgeous cinematography and production design, and - amid all the madness - genuinely thought-provoking themes that deserve serious reflection.\n\nAs expected, the cast is phenomenal. Emma Stone, Jesse Plemons, and Aidan Delbis all deliver award-worthy performances. It might not be Stone's most out-there role (a tough bar at this point), but Plemons reaches new career heights.\n\nThe movie builds to an explosive ending that I absolutely loved - one that will undoubtedly divide audiences. But honestly, aren't those the best kind?"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "1d54807f-3408-4dcb-876d-faaa06d62210", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "89640f0fb661ecc98713a9099e066fb32c3aae9f1842d5432b3910cc6d282dc3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "ntomic-499-716183", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-12-24", "title": null, "content": "Amazing actors, superb tension is created along the entire movie, OST is good, art direction was beautiful. Why turn all of that upside down to turn this movie into either a mockery to the audience or a boringly trivial political point at best?\n\nThe ending not only felt unnecessary but poorly developed. Why was Michelle even threatened by Teddy if they had superior technology? Why did she decide to wipe out humanity after all if Teddy was actually someone who, apparently, showed integrity after all? (had a bad childhood, lived poorly, decided to castrate himself, all in order to intercede in the name of all humans for them to be left alone)\n\nThis just feels stupid."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "437edb9d-64f0-45fa-a6a7-cba0f18158dd", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b82bdfb286cf0529e3e5f8190ec6310baab909d499f41c7292d04ad42998ee02"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "smeesheady", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-12-14", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia mistakes endless dialogue for depth. What starts as an intriguing premise quickly collapses into a long, claustrophobic talking exercise that overstays its welcome by a wide margin.\n\nThe film is painfully slow, spending nearly an hour circling the same conversations in a single location without meaningful escalation. Characters repeat ideas instead of developing them, and tension never properly builds. Instead of suspense, you get monotony. Instead of mystery, you get lectures.\n\nYes, the movie is trying to be philosophical and satirical - but philosophy without momentum is just noise. The runtime feels inflated for no reason other than self-indulgence. This story could have been told in under 90 minutes with far more impact.\n\nThe late-game payoff doesn't justify the slog. By the time the film reveals its hand, many viewers will already be exhausted or checked out. Slow cinema can be powerful, but Bugonia confuses slowness with substance.\n\nIn the end, it feels like a festival film designed to be admired rather than enjoyed - more interested in sounding smart than actually engaging its audience."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7d4aa74c-067a-42f1-b8c6-2ab25ba7c77a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7f0f3d85a9cd0ea5365b0a091cbe0254605a57918ecc000b6f3ccd94ac568579"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Sleepin_Dragon", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "Teddy and Don mount an audacious attempt to kidnap Michelle Fuller, the CEO of a huge pharmaceutical company - and the very company Teddy works for. The question is simple enough: why has he kidnapped her?\n\nThis film has restored my faith in cinema. It's original, fresh, amusing and dark. A genre-hopper that works surprisingly well, it plays as a black comedy, a satire of conspiracy culture, and a tense thriller in places.\n\nI found myself laughing at some very unexpected moments, often followed by a slight sense of guilt. The film also dips unapologetically into some very dark places.\n\nControl and abuse sit at the heart of the film, with poor Don almost entirely subjugated by his cousin. The dynamic between them is uncomfortable, but deliberately so, and it adds an extra layer of unease beneath the humour.\n\nWhat's so utterly brilliant is that Teddy's obsession with Michelle's origins feels completely unhinged - yet somewhere at the back of your mind, that nagging question remains. Even while telling yourself there's less than a one percent chance he's right, the film keeps you curious.\n\nI think the ending will divide opinion. I loved it, and felt it was perfectly in keeping with the tone of the film, though I can understand why it won't work for everyone. Personally, I adored the tea cosy on the head.\n\nThe acting is outstanding across the board. Emma Stone, as expected, is superb - not just in delivery, but in her physicality and movement, which are remarkable. Credit to her for continuing to choose films that are a little left field.\n\nJesse Plemons is phenomenal, delivering an unforgettable performance, while Aidan Delbis deserves real praise for bringing Don to life with such vulnerability.\n\nIs every conspiracy theorist wrong about everything? It's enough to make you raise an eyebrow.\n\n8/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "d3371962-e999-4e5a-aec5-3db7b831b78a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "a53ab0df196f49d66d5c02600c3cb3e9b5c2e453ce5c0a42a89354a4789f9733"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "kevin_robbins", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-06", "title": null, "content": "I recently watched Bugonia (2025) on Peacock. The storyline follows a successful pharmaceutical CEO who is kidnapped by two men convinced she is an alien. Believing she must be tortured until she reveals the location of her spaceship, they take her captive. Can she escape her kidnappers-or is she truly something not of this world?\n\nThe film is directed by Yorgos Lanthimos (The Lobster) and stars Emma Stone (La La Land), Jesse Plemons (Civil War), and Aidan Delbis.\n\nThis is one of those films where a cloud of mystery hangs over the story from beginning to end. The writing is sharp that you're never quite sure what will happen-or to whom-at any given moment. Long stretches of dialogue, thoughtful world-building, and strange subplots keep you invested throughout, while gradually revealing how we arrived here and why. The performances are elite across the board, though you may find yourself not truly rooting for anyone. The cinematography, background sound design, and score do an excellent job of building tension. The action and kill scenes are top-tier, featuring impressive practical effects and gore. As everything builds, the finale lands perfectly, delivering a mind-boggling conclusion that neatly closes the story arc.\n\nIn conclusion, Bugonia pairs an engaging premise with brilliant execution. I'd score it an 8/10 and strongly recommend it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8ac3ea61-00c0-43b8-8bc5-aaa291135fa4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "30e498bd1b7ef2fb41f8a80e7c0402535a932b588982d016e866c84e754795b3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "business-33778", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-03", "title": null, "content": "'Bugonia' is another wild, out-there film that has a lot to say about many subjects, but fails to capitalize on what it sets up in the end, and with a strange score and presentation, it struggles to really show what type of film it was really trying to be.\n\nEmma Stone is solid, but Jesse Plemons is the one who really does the heavy lifting in this film, delivering a layered, emotional, and outstanding performance that should have him on everyone's radar come award season.\n\nIt had our attention for most of the film, but an oddly placed side story with a police officer that really didn't add to the film, and a really out-there ending left us feeling a bit let down. These films are not for everyone, and Bugonia is another one that will have that big divide between those who love it and those who really didn't enjoy it at all. It's a tough one to be anywhere in the middle on.\n\n'Bugonia' had us in the first half, with a fantastic performance by Jesse Plemons, but really lost us with the absurd and out-there ending that the more we thought about, left us really surprised at how much it affected our enjoyment of everything else in the film.\n\nBrad: 6.5 Josh: 6\n\nFull Review: wbtp.link/youtube."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ecde4a85-6950-4c3b-824c-03ab28d4a75c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "eae53aa30fde16bc18098a278b1cb054c8cc4915349a1e2fb19a3ee841608be7"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "jordanbutler1996", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-11-16", "title": null, "content": "Emma Stone is that girl, I love what working with Yorgos brings out in her. Jessie Plemons was great too. I enjoyed that you could see how both characters got to where they were, what they had to gain and lose and as a result rooted for and detested both in different ways. It does this and then was still brave enough to take a stance.\n\nI think at its core the movie wasn't toying with any groundbreaking material or fresh ideas, but what made this so interesting was the brave and bold choices Yorgos made. At every turn it felt as though he chose to do the most interesting thing, which made it feel like a fresh take. This really made for interesting post-movie discussions.\n\nI do think that it could've used a slightly shorter runtime, but no major qualms given the payoff was worth it. I also felt that the cousin character wasn't utilised well enough to justify his presence, even though I understand he has a purpose in the dynamic. In my eyes, who just took up valuable time that could've been used for more Emma Stone dialogue.\n\nOverall, great film, very much recommend."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "0c708f73-a8a0-4c0b-86d3-b9555fc1d350", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "28758dae58137d017efe1d314f7dcc8ddc546b74598f87029b5d912f924e013b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "jenelmer1", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-08", "title": null, "content": "The whole movie makes me writhe with discomfort. The way it is shot it so close and detailed that it makes every humans seem alien. It puts you on edge. Emma Stone has been a long time favorite who just seems to get better with every single role. But let's talk about Jesse Plemmons. He is a chameleon. He can take any role and make it uncomfortable or become your best friend. I have never seen him excel as he does in this role. He is so very easy to hate, so disconcerting, and yet somehow makes his character just the smallest bit relatable so that you aren't just watching from a far, you are kind of IN the crazy with him has the movie progresses. It's a seriously hilarious film. You can watch it and make it all serious, all funny, or enjoy the combination. But you cannot disregard the talent of the story telling. An absolute masterful example of acting and directing. Thank you to everyone who contributed to this production. Last minute shout out to the costumes, they don't quite design the film, but the term \"influence\" would be an understatement."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a8c7110c-967b-4084-87d8-9cbc172f5c7b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "efccc104b857491c44bc94b0737c62b35f7c97c75230e1f38ea2a76de5f10b27"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "pedroquintaoo", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-02", "title": null, "content": "\"Bugonia\" is one of those films that confirms Yorgos Lanthimos still has a distinct cinematic voice - but sometimes that's not enough to keep us hooked from start to finish. After the visual and emotional delirium of Poor Things, it was impossible not to set high expectations. Here, Lanthimos once again dives into absurdity and dark humor, but his eccentricity feels more restrained, as if the film drifts somewhere between satire and boredom. I honestly think that trimming about 20 minutes would've helped - maybe even kept me from dozing off for five.\n\nThere's an intriguing commentary on fanaticism and how certain online communities impose their beliefs and conspiracy theories. The director seems to point his finger at collective stupidity, but halfway through, the pace drags. There are clever ideas, solid performances - Emma Stone, Jesse Plemons, and Aidan Delbis carry the story - yet the film gets somewhat lost in its own strangeness. It's as if Lanthimos had a clear vision of what he wanted to say, but not how to keep the audience awake until he gets there.\n\nIn the final stretch, when the narrative finally loosens up and that peculiar absurd tone takes over, the film starts to breathe, to feel alive again... and, ironically, that's when it ends. Bugonia feels like it had everything to become provocative and memorable, but it stops halfway.\n\nIt's not a disaster - far from it - but it's not one of those experiences that lingers after the credits roll. Somewhere between discomfort and apathy, Bugonia entertains, but never quite fascinates."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cadb0d8d-5c72-4a98-a53a-ffcbfda852ef", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "64ce049d0c31645f9bad49f32ab9d9a9d10522c8ad110cb4ca746d0ac97e673d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Medo-karim", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia dares to flip the traditional alien-invasion narrative on its head. Instead of focusing on high-tech extraterrestrial dominance, Yorgos Lanthimos explores something far more unsettling: what if the \"aliens\" are not cold, emotionless invaders - but beings who feel deeply, bleed, suffer, and judge us based on our own failures?\n\nThe film blends dark humor with disturbing psychological tension, forcing the audience to constantly question who the real threat is - the supposed alien, or the humans driven by fear and conspiracy. Emma Stone gives a brilliantly layered performance, switching effortlessly between vulnerability and otherworldly superiority.\n\nVisually and thematically bold, Bugonia offers a refreshing and provocative take on humanity's place in the universe - and whether we deserve it. It's the kind of sci-fi that lingers in your mind long after the credits roll."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "59693fcb-2a27-44cc-9c51-9947a338df92", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b29597a3e361d7962b1955ce91e9d804f3570deb2e274d72b45fa2f65e28d6ae"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "eoinageary", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-02", "title": null, "content": "CEO Michelle is kidnapped by two conspiracy theorists Teddy and Don who believe she is an alien blending in to society and ruling over humanity. Their aim is to extract information about the mothership and rid earth of the Aliens, Michelle must adapt fast and fight for her life.\n\nI'm over and back with this one a bit, firstly what I liked a lot about it was the acting, Emma stone was great but Jesse Plemons was the stand out. The character is very well done, the first half hour you just think he's a conspiracy nut but that movie reveals a lot of layers in his life, traumas and how he got to this point and manipulating his cousin.\n\nI want to say I called the ending hahaha the movie is littered with metaphorical messages, I won't detail as there are spoiler but to do with how we no matter how much we are told, ruin this planet, how others try and try yet many countries are ecological terrorists and do nothing to help, how humans treat each other, it's all downhill.\n\nIt's good, it's weird, awesome soundtrack and shots, 6.5/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c9bbaee7-ca63-42aa-a7eb-e30a7508cb3f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "67418ea0db344b299ce0245246c68983b7f0aa69bdb380c44e8747b4fc645506"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "XE_Kilroy", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-11-04", "title": null, "content": "I went into Bugonia without having seen the original Korean film it's based on (Save the Green Planet!), but even without that comparison point, this remake is a misfire from start to finish. What could have been a sharp satire ended up as a frustratingly juvenile film instead.\n\nFrom the outset, the film struggles to justify its own premise. We're told in the synopsis that two men are convinced the CEO of a pharmaceutical company is an alien. But the storytelling never lays groundwork for that belief. There's no buildup, no evidence, no psychological exploration --- just a scattered, generalized conversation between the two men with abrupt cross-cutting to the woman in question going about her day, followed by a very sudden kidnapping. The audience is left bewildered why she's targeted, or why they believe she's an alien, and the narrative offers no breadcrumbs to follow.\n\nOnly much later do we learn that the CEO is connected to the men thru their dying mother, whose illness was allegedly caused by a drug manufactured by the company. This revelation would have been better served as the emotional and narrative foundation of the film, not a later stage casual info drop. Had that connection been established early, with some parallel to the alien angle, we might have had a chance to understand their paranoia or empathize with their motivations.\n\nThe script is another casualty. Dialogue thruout the film is either clunky or childish, never once landing with wit or weight. And while the portrayal of conspiracy theorists is meant to be exaggerated for effect, it is caricature so extreme it becomes offensive. The film parodies rather than explores their character, which only sabotages any thematic depth it might have been aiming for.\n\nVisually, there are moments of enjoyment. The litany of tracking shots, in particular, are well-executed and add a sense of style to an otherwise mediocre storyboard.\n\nBy the time the big twist arrives --- one that's so telegraphed it barely qualifies as a twist --- I was already long disengaged. Bugonia wants to be provocative, and emotionally or intellectually resonant, but it only comes across as insulting and imbecilic. I left the theater actually disgusted, relieved that the ordeal was finally over."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "42f428ad-c0c1-4321-913a-7454d600087d", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "13ee19cbaf4bd339bd84e04e313c8a424ff4489e9b3f9575fb84c99ed445e2a8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "steiner-sam", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-14", "title": null, "content": "It's a sci-fi dramatic comedy drama set over four days in the present, somewhere in North America. Devoted conspiracy theorist Teddy Gatz (Jesse Plemons) and his cognitively limited cousin, Don (Aidan Delbis), kidnap the dominating CEO of a major pharmaceutical company, Michelle Fuller (Emma Stone). Teddy and Don believe she is an alien from the Andromeda Galaxy who is trying to destroy humanity. Teddy wants to appeal to the Andromedan emperor when the mothership comes to Earth in four days during a lunar eclipse. Most of the film takes place after the kidnapping in Teddy's rural home, where he also tends beehives in which the bees seem to be dying. During the film, we learn the background to Teddy's beliefs, and also meet a dimwitted deputy sheriff (Stavros Halkias) who has a history with Teddy's family.\n\n\"Bugonia\" is hard to describe. Is it comedy? Is it sci-fi? Is it drama? Is it a documentary? It's not laugh-out-loud comedy, but there are many satiric send-ups. But there is shocking and violent drama as well, and a definite tip of the cap to science fiction. And I know there are at least a few people who will assume \"Bugonia\" is a description of reality. Jesse Plemons and Emma Stone are outstanding, and they dominate the entire movie. Lanthimos's direction and the movie's pace are excellent. For me, \"Bugonia\" was a very satisfying movie experience."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "442cd13a-5e2e-437a-9638-374ba297e6dc", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8fcc3ab0a3aa952898d256fd9e5fb987452a3bc978689022db63d5d38d5050e4"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "williambertram", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-30", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is a dark (VERY dark in some places) comedy / sci-fi story involving a conspiracy theorist who thinks Andromedins have invaded the Earth.\n\nPerformances are hit and miss. I'm sure some of this has to do with the writing, but Aidan Delbis didn't pull off the \"challenged partner-in-crime.\" He was doing something with his lip that reminded me of Bill Murray in Caddyshack. Given that the movie is so dark, I think they could have written this character as someone with a legitimate mental illness, and have it portrayed that way, preferably by someone else. The comedic angle of this character fell flat. This same character type was played straight in the movie Good Time to a much greater effect.\n\nI also think Teddy was far too stupid to have pulled any of this off. Jesse Plemons did a serviceable job playing Jesse, but the character was written to be too unintelligent.\n\nOverall, this was a decent movie. The ending was a little opaque, but it's easy enough to follow the general idea without Googling.\n\n8/10."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "72ed78b2-9343-4127-a460-3504ecd4529c", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "8725f72d8b00af9af3c4f6facc73c3d0c04eea7a518deea4b530c330da2d9ab8"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Navid94", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-01", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is one of those rare films that starts with absolute mastery. The first two acts are everything I love about psychological thrillers: sharp tension, claustrophobic atmosphere, unpredictable character dynamics, and powerhouse performances from Jesse Plemons and Emma Stone. The film grips you immediately and holds you tightly with its intensity, mystery, and emotional unease. For a long while, it feels like it's building toward something truly great.\n\nAnd then... the ending arrives.\n\nUp until the final stretch, the film is grounded in psychological realism. Teddy's paranoia, Don's uncertainty, Michelle's unsettling composure; these elements create a fascinating ambiguity. We don't know what's real, and that's exactly what makes the film so effective. Lanthimos sets up a moral and emotional battlefield where truth is uncertain, and madness and ideology become indistinguishable.\n\nBut the final twist breaks everything.\n\nThe moment the film reveals that Teddy's most bizarre, delusional, conspiracy-theory fantasies were all literally true, the story collapses. Details he could never possibly know; alien biology, communication methods, spaceship design; suddenly become fact. The movie abandons all psychological depth and logic, replacing it with an absurdist sci-fi punchline that feels unearned. Instead of confronting paranoia, insanity, or political extremism, the film simply turns the conspiracy into reality, and the thematic resonance evaporates.\n\nEven worse, the ending reduces complex characters into caricatures: the \"paranoid man\" becomes a prophet, the ambiguous hostage becomes a literal alien overlord, and the entire world becomes a kind of surreal joke. For a film that spent so long building genuine tension and nuanced conflict, the final twist feels like a betrayal of its own intelligence.\n\nIt's a shame, because so much of Bugonia is fantastic; the acting, the atmosphere, the direction. The beginning and middle are gripping and at times brilliant. But the ending undercuts the emotional investment and turns a potentially great thriller into something tonally confused and logically hollow.\n\nA powerful film with incredible potential; but ultimately undone by a twist that trades meaning for shock value."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "3ef2358b-14fb-4b4e-bf38-7c98adf13752", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "d24ce079dfa84687ed2a619058e0d607fdf01efd9a0b021c8d8058e93cd081af"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "LisaGuiaTO", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-12-10", "title": null, "content": "I watched Bugonia last night and was happily surprised, what a great film! Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons were absolutely incredible. Plemons honestly deserves an Oscar for this performance.\n\nEmma's acting style here even reminded me a bit of Tilda Swinton (one of my favourites) , that same unusual spark she brings to every scene.\n\nThe movie is such a perfect blend of sci-fi, horror, comedy, and drama. I only wish the directing had been a little more upbeat at times, as a few moments felt a bit flat... but the finale completely elevates the whole experience.\n\nHighly recommend it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "cfd019cf-2dcc-4e53-88d3-013dc7c18690", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "af783c52db2b71dff59161f90ae1ab4246136cf90ade1cd69b48b91ef7696e5d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "lvrbellini", "rating": 7, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "The movie is fantastic and I liked it... but that ending... it could've landed better tho\n\nThere are a few pivotal moments where the drama felt underused.\n\nFor example, the storyline about the Police Officer abusing Teddy when he was younger had the potential to deepen her psychological fragility, but it never fully paid off. Also the scene where Teddy kills his mother in the hospital also lacked the emotional conflict and raw tension it deserved; it could've been far more dramatic and impactful maybe conflicting a nurse or something\n\nAnd the ending? It really should've been left open to interpretation. Keeping it ambiguous would have preserved the intensity of the drama and kept the audience debating: \"Did she lose her mind after everything... or was she truly an alien?\"\n\nCongrats to the director that got us talking about it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "e5a1edb2-dbe3-4797-bb90-f5997082f0a4", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f864daf849784f3e75a195042accd89a55e6fabe99340a7080f027bd09721cf9"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "VasileiosK-6", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-18", "title": null, "content": "So many things to think about after this movie: human nature, environmental crisis, extraterrestrial life, social inequality, political correctness. The screenplay is incrediby witty and the directing just captivating. Amazing music (especially Dietrich's \"where have all the flowers gone\") and superb acting. Emma Stone is fantastic as always, but I'm really rooting for Jesse Plemmons to win the Oscar this year."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "a06648fc-8a43-4168-b368-99a09d3729fa", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f109440711eb2c8d10656d944e81c04bcffbe6d861ebcd974e9febdce0912da5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "cjonesas", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-04", "title": null, "content": "Thought it would be more groundbreaking and impactful, but it was just another weird movie of recent years. Needed to be more horrific and realistic with tougher situations and way better visual effects.\n\nAll the good acting is just lost in that alien intelligence script.\n\nEspecially, the ending that I suspected at 30% wasn't as tough and mind boggling that I expected.\n\nSeriously needs a sequel with dramatic humanoids in full motion together with that dense lady."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c7b0477c-9ea7-4d60-b0fc-95895b0ee662", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "64d720b90de119c6b4e93f613877e62cf485841b76f82987dc2050be628ebaef"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "stevenjkc", "rating": 8, "date": "2026-01-04", "title": null, "content": "This was a nice surprise of a movie. Did not know that it was a remake of a South Korean film but it humour definitely fits with South Korean cinema. Jesse Plemens and Emma Stone as lead actors did a fantastic job. The actor who played the cousin was also incredible. All in all a solid movie which I would recommend."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "c4a09756-9394-4bb3-8b04-72d3e0995e45", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6fe0048f01f751fd1e886ab0d91fab3bb3fecb0486ad8a2bf2d7c21734300bf3"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "laylajo11", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-29", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia stood out to me specifically because I don't think I have ever watched a movie quite like it. From the unique, almost vertical shots of cinematography to the long lines of dialogue without any cutaways or even music in the backgrounds it offers a very raw type of movie.\n\nI typically tend to enjoy movies with so much emphasis on the character's depth and their dynamics with others in the movie, but for some reason it fell a bit flat for me. I think that the story had a lot of potential, but I think that potential was built too long until I was starting to become somewhat bored.\n\nThat being said, once it picked up, it was as if a flip had switched. (if you watched the movie, I assume you know the scene I'm talking about). I was genuinely intrigued by the movie and the acting was really good as well, and by the end of it I liked the direction the movie had taken.\n\nOverall, I liked the movie but it didn't stand out to me and I thought the build up took too long."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "15067396-11d7-484e-9870-7e901f6d9d29", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "78c2962477a65d33f1341e144928f785e2cba7c14fdd1e541ce021c8dbc8505e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "nielsjo-klein", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-11-01", "title": null, "content": "This movie has nothing to it. It is not funny. It does not keep you in suspense. The story isn't captivating. The atmosphere is just lame. Me and my wife went to see this in a cinema: complete waste of time and 24 euros. We both hated it, worse than throwing up from Baileys Irish cream. It was just bad, bad, bad."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "8a1cbd35-ccb0-4220-b4ad-a5fe8bddd896", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b051ea944e12ee99b1689a71b96e90c57568c273d828e2038f72a2aef25ad0b1"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "jorgenbostrom", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-27", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is a brilliant, unsettling, and strangely beautiful film, carried by performances that feel raw and completely lived in.\n\nThe cast moves from paranoia to quiet reflection with a level of control that gives the story real weight. The chemistry between the leads feels genuine, and the supporting actors deepen the sense of a world that is both familiar and quietly slipping out of joint.\n\nAt its core, Bugonia delivers a calm but brutal truth: the planet will endure. Long after humans exhaust themselves with fear, ego, and bad decisions, Earth will keep turning. Life will adapt, evolve, and carry on without us. The film never lectures; it lets its imagery and characters speak for themselves, and the result is powerful.\n\nEmma Stone is phenomenal here, easily worthy of an Academy Award. And maybe even for the director, whose vision ties every piece together with precision and purpose."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ff36fb37-a273-4d67-ae81-ca647404bd4f", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "c791b507429b16267ae39a16557c6da52e619baf2236efeaab403b2fe424fe8f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "felix_lechat", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-10-26", "title": null, "content": "The premise of a kidnapping sets the stage for relentless tension, with power dynamics bubbling up and exploding like a pressure cooker throughout the film.\n\nWhat struck me most was the brilliant duality between Michelle: the wealthy, hyper-educated liberal vs Teddy: the poor, conspiracy-driven incel (along with his cousin). Their exchanges mirror the polarized conversations we so often hear today between the progressive left and the reactionary right, where both sides speak but no one truly listens.\n\nIt's an incredibly fertile setup. A sharp reflection of our times, where extreme views dominate the airwaves and common ground seems impossible, even as we all share the same fragile planet, one whose survival depends on our ability to rethink how we consume its resources.\n\nThe three lead actors deliver outstanding performances, capturing every flicker of discomfort, fear, and rage so vividly that the audience can't help but squirm in their seats.\n\nWithout spoiling the ending, I'll just say it's undeniably original, though for me, it strays from the rich ideological duel that powers the story up to that point.\n\nStill, Bugonia is an absolute must-see. A gripping, provocative, and brilliantly acted film with Oscar-worthy performances."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "7752c3d0-5fa8-401e-a31a-99b34aa461c6", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "3df19f87ea3922bb5a59306041744f6ada42d385257120174ea69799eba3ae3e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "yothisisyo", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-09", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia's commentary on social/cultural/existential aspects of human life loses all it's effect with that climax , may be that's the commentary ? The Insane people are right and normal people are insane ? Seems too far-fetched for me because the point it's trying to make actually lands halfway through. Why would the Film-maker kill everything he actually made. On a Side note, This is a proper Upendra kind of ending I prefer it when Upendra does it I dont hate it here but it felt odd."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "43313c31-efb1-4c51-9d33-8e1664173c9a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "b7564fa857c1f54791b42d0d793323e6a78e27f2a722fa25899fc53dcad30147"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "bankofmarquis", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-20", "title": null, "content": "Say what you will about Greek Director Yorgos Lanthimos and the oddities that are his films, but one thing you can NOT say about his films is that they are mundane.\n\nThe latest outing by the Director of POOR THINGS, a \"two-hander\" starring Lanthimos' stock players Emma Stone (POOR THINGS) and Jesse Plemons (KINDS OF KINDNESS) is a case in point.\n\nBUGONIA tells the tale of High Profile, High-Scale Tech CEO Michelle (Stone) who is kidnapped by Teddy (Plemons) because Teddy thinks that Michelle is an alien (the outer space kind).\n\nWhat results over the next 2 hours or so, is a cat and mouse game between Michelle and Teddy, told mostly through dialogue between the two that sometimes veers onto the absurb, but almost always finds the humanity of the characters in a world that Lanthimos posits has lost it's humanity.\n\nIt's a fascinating character study amongst a strong condemnation of our world today that is wrapped in a oddly entertaining romp thanks to the works of the two leads.\n\nThis film could have easily devolved quickly into over-acting, boredom and way-too-over-the-top absurdism if it weren't for the grounded performances of both Stone and Plemons. I've been a big fan of both performers for quite some time and Stone (with her 2 Oscars) most certainly has the credentials and heft for this type of film, but it is the work of Plemons that really pops out as he lays out his conspiracy theory to Stone in such a level-headed, thought through way that one thinks, from the beginning, that Plemons might be RIGHT and not CRAZY. Both performances are Oscar-nominee worthy.\n\nThese two characters are wrapped up and steered through this world with a sure hand from Lanthimos who actually shows some restraint in his absurb commentary of the world, while also pointing out the hypocrisies and foibles of modern civilization.\n\nThis one won't be for every one and the ending has a twist that I felt made the journey worthwhile, but some will not (I'm sure).\n\nIt's another headtrip by Lanthimos hosted by Stone and Plemons...and they are very pleasing hosts, indeed.\n\nLetter Grade: A-\n\n8 stars (out of 10) and you can take that to the Bank (ofMarquis)"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9b1f7eca-445b-449a-94de-ecb8034fc100", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6ff7f4be701338fe5e15c4b0ee2c23be6fcbf553e76b32bdf62d5c8a416e4a6b"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "TheSilverStreak", "rating": 6, "date": "2026-01-02", "title": null, "content": "We watched this a few nights ago, so I've had a little time to process my thoughts on this. In short, the premise was good, the performances by the three principle actors were great, but I was really disappointed with the ending. It contained an incredible buildup and then seemed to lose its production values. I thought it significantly detracted from the overall impact of the film."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "dd0ca3a7-5905-4319-b906-94e8018172b9", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "7644269eaba24d61f5460cda5af3198bf14dd23842255061212d1e8a22ed5fd7"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "SpyroDungeon", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-10-31", "title": null, "content": "Yorgos Lanthimos returns with a new film, and we see Emma Stone and Jesse Plemons again, a reunion of similar casts. After Kinds of Kindness, the cast remains the same, and it delves into the same surrealist narratives as those films, a surrealist narrative we witness in real life.\n\nIn our lives, we witness the difficulties of life and the forces that try to influence it. Our lives are invaded, and people spout various conspiracy theories in response. Although some people call them lies, and they are subjected to various codes by the authorities, Yorgos, instead of considering the possibility of lies, asks us to ask, \"What if it's not a lie?\" and \"How do we define madness?\" Contrary to these questions, the film gives you a taste of the mystery and leads you to a striking point where you constantly ask, \"Conspiracy theories are lies.\" Bugonia, on the contrary, suggests that it's not a lie, but perhaps it could be true. Of course, he brilliantly presents this with dark humor and Yorgos's dialogue. On top of that, he is a wonderful governed/manager and goes into detail about being condemned to oppression and not being able to escape from it.\n\nBugonia will challenge your values __and morals.\n\nA film that will challenge your perspectives will make you wonder, perhaps even hope the Illuminati is real, and perhaps even consider UFO religions.\n\n\"Why isn't the concept of absurd relevant?\"\n\nWill the equation of superiority and weakness hold true for this logic? Human indifference to power and the cosmic universe, and of course, Bugonia will give you a taste of cosmic nihilism, and it will show you nihilism.\n\nThe universe doesn't even care about you, and there will always be someone stronger than you.\n\n\"I will always be superior, and you will always be oppressed.\""}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "88420120-1b22-4d9a-8504-f6852ab48f33", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "dfbb5a7b87d7c449c342ffe355152b53b574d789ec82ec5dbda2f68256c87c9f"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "harryphiliphudson", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-03", "title": null, "content": "Biggest slap in the face I've received since the game of thrones. Brilliant performances from Emma stone and Jesse Plemons . Both of whom have been given a good smack in the face from a director that they're too loyal to . I've given a 6 because it's worth a watch just please god turn it off with about 20 minutes to go. You'll know when . This is the first review I've written in about 7 years so let that tell you what you want ."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5ef21ec8-dbfa-4b56-bdf3-d1af769628e7", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6fa6ad8856ad22b8944b79025c6511ecfa691eec1f30a17b7465d25a10eab9cc"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "sami2005", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is one of those rare films that manages to blend style, tension, and emotional depth into a single captivating experience. From its opening moments, the movie establishes a unique tone that mixes mystery with psychological intensity, gradually pulling the viewer deeper into its world. What makes Bugonia especially remarkable is how it balances its narrative confidence with unexpected surprises-culminating in a finale that is truly unpredictable and leaves a lingering impact.\n\nOne of the strongest aspects of the film is the dynamic between Emma and Jessie. Their conversations are sharp, layered, and filled with subtle tension. Whether they are confronting each other, sharing vulnerable moments, or unraveling pieces of the story, their dialogue remains consistently gripping. The chemistry between the two actresses elevates the emotional stakes of every scene, making even the quiet moments feel charged and meaningful. Their exchanges become the driving force of the film, keeping the audience constantly engaged.\n\nThe soundtrack deserves special recognition as well. The music in Bugonia is not only beautiful-it is deeply expressive and perfectly aligned with the film's emotional beats. Each track seems carefully chosen to enhance the atmosphere, whether it's heightening suspense, deepening a dramatic moment, or adding warmth to a more intimate scene. The score becomes a character of its own, guiding the viewer through the story with elegance and precision.\n\nVisually, the film is equally impressive. Its cinematography and pacing create a smooth rhythm that supports the unfolding mystery without ever feeling rushed or predictable. And just when the audience thinks they understand where the story is headed, Bugonia delivers a twist that is both shocking and satisfying.\n\nOverall, Bugonia is a beautifully crafted, emotionally rich film that stands out for its performances, writing, and exceptional music. It is a must-watch and one of the year's pleasant surprises."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "000ee6e0-549d-41cf-9d4b-ee771fedb57a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "aa38beceb81bb06b3cb316931eae4f03bd46e001cc159f870d64c9c2f9deda85"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Tweetienator", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-12-10", "title": null, "content": "To watch Emma Stone is always a pleasure; sadly, Bugonia is a rather mediocre movie, or better, a mixed experience. For example: the \"twist\" is no twist. After the \"theory\" of our two \"heroes\" was exposed, I did know what was coming. My main trouble with this movie is that it is too long, and having to listen to all that \"blah blah,\" especially in the beginning, was rather a nauseating experience - just compare it with the start of Fight Club, and you know how interesting and even mind-blowing such an exposition can be. Some cutting may do wonders to this flick. Anyway, there are a few funny and even great scenes, and I liked Emma Stone's performance a lot. But whereas, e.g., Poor Things I will put on my screens again, this one I doubt. Verdict: not too bad, but not too good either."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "6415f5f1-0a0a-4f08-a81b-4adbb9532620", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "639dffd58fd74402f65ddf016d19a9f51d1c1f4bd04eddbcaca6d62c8e275089"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "bceast", "rating": 1, "date": "2025-11-03", "title": null, "content": "Ridiculous plot, boring, hollow and hard to watch. Not a moment of pleasure in the whole movie except maybe that the end is so silly that my wife and I laughed out loud. Even the score/music was bad. I am shocked that Emma Stone agreed to be in this movie. I think it was so bad some critics thought it must have a deeper meaning. It doesn't, Skip it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "5dc5f7b4-7ec3-43c8-a3e1-c6953ae061d8", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "637371a4bca2a304e618a5f291dd154e62fe3b1b78d3013a8fdb18ad4529b26e"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "neildvinton-25278", "rating": 9, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "Just been blew away. My first review as I can't believe it's only getting a 7.6... It's simply brilliant and I'd say on par with the usual suspects for the way the film plays you. Loved it. Simmons is a legend. He can do everything.\n\nReally thought it wasn't going to add upto much at the beginning but wow, haha then the ride began. It's in my top 5 films. It's so well done and clever. Don't read any spoilers just watch it."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "193e2bd6-062d-4e69-882c-b4fdb9f39f2a", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "06b10eaa9f2f2cfe05d9a695e5ee6fbb18a0df0502a1ecda0ce162e3f2b202a5"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "arungeorge13", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-25", "title": null, "content": "Ven as the American remake of 2003's bizarre South Korean sci-fi comedy Save the Green Planet!, the Yorgos Lanthimos flick has more to offer in 2025 to a world that has seemingly recovered from a pandemic, yet is completely LOST in how to be HUMAN. The three main characters here are a big pharma company's CEO Michelle Fuller (Emma \"bald is the new sexy\" Stone), conspiracy theorist Teddy Gatz (Jesse Plemons, in one of his most superlative performances) and his autistic cousin Don (Aidan Delbis, a breakout effort from an actor who's actually on the autism spectrum). Yes, the premise is absurd, but it's also in the absurdist-loving hands of Yorgos Lanthimos.. so, what do you expect?\n\nSurprisingly, Bugonia happens to be Lanthimos' most accessible film thus far. It leans into the bizarre, of course, but more than two-thirds of the film is actually a hostage thriller with plenty of conversational exchanges. This gives writer Will Tracy the opportunity to put out some sensationally sharp satire on the state of corporatism, how the poor continue to get obliterated in modern society, how the ability to make life-altering decisions lay in the hands of a powerful few, how humans are just eventual lab-rats for \"experiments,\" and many such deep perspectives.\n\nThe finale can have multiple interpretations too (..not going to spoil it). However, I'll go ahead and admit that I found the \"CEO in captivity\" portions the most intriguing. Plemons is an unstoppable force here, and equally matched with a red-hot, dominating energy by Stone. DoP Robbie Ryan, collaborating with Lanthimos for the third time since Poor Things), conjures up some intense VistaVision magic, while Jerskin Fendrix's unconventional (and orchestral) score serves as a special ingredient. If you're familiar with Lanthimos' generally nihilistic approach to storytelling, Bugonia should very much be up your alley."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "deb9c3b9-1b0d-472c-b2aa-f5f24ec963ce", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "1b7b6ab6705421603f8f9628ab39bfb68fcfc23672bb5630b38d53112e797f8c"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "jboothmillard", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-11-02", "title": null, "content": "I found out from reading more about it that this was an English-language remake of the South Korean film Save the Green Planet! After watching the original, I was most looking forward to this version from one of my favourite modern filmmakers, similar to David Lynch and Tim Burton, director Yorgos Lanthimos (The Lobster, The Favourite, Poor Things, Kinds of Kindness). Basically, Teddy Gatz (Jesse Plemons) is a conspiracy theorist beekeeper, and lives in a messy farmhouse with his intellectually disabled cousin Don (Aidan Delbis). They have a plan that they believe will save the world. Michelle Fuller (Emma Stone) is the wealthy CEO of pharmaceutical company Auxolith. When she arrives at her mansion, Teddy and Don, disguised with masks of Jennifer Aniston, attempt to abduct her. She struggles against them and almost escapes, but they pin her down and knock her unconscious. Driving back to their farmhouse, Don shaves all of Michelle's hair off. The cousins hold Michelle captive in the basement of the farmhouse, and she is covered in an antihistamine cream. When she wakes and finds her hair missing, Teddy tells her that her hair was destroyed so that she cannot communicate with her mothership. Teddy is convinced that Michelle is part of an invasive alien species, the \"Andromedans\", who have infiltrated the human race. He intends to use Michelle as a bargaining tool to demand that the aliens leave Earth, and that there are four days until a lunar eclipse, which will allow them to enter Earth's atmosphere undetected. Michelle insists that she is not an alien, but she will not be released until she does what he asks. Michelle tries to bargain, threaten, and then play along to appease Teddy, but without any success. Flashbacks (in black-and-white) reveal Teddy's mother, Sandy (Alicia Silverstone), was a test subject for one of Auxolith's drugs, which resulted in her falling into a coma. Michelle covered up the incident and now funds Sandy's treatment in a nearby hospital; there are several scenes of Sandy's comatose body levitating in the air. Michelle is reported missing, and her disappearance becomes international news. Teddy continues to work at Auxolith as a warehouse worker while Don stays at the farmhouse to guard Michelle. While a police hunt begins, Teddy has a tense encounter with Casey (Stavros Halkias), the local sheriff; Casey used to babysit him as a boy and molested him, and he wants to make amends. Teddy and Don continue their interrogation of Michelle, but are unable to get her to confess to being an alien. Michelle notices Don is apprehensive about Teddy's plan and attempts to convince him to free her. While torturing her via electroshock, Teddy theorises that Michelle is a high-ranking member of the Andromedans due to her high pain tolerance and brings her upstairs for dinner. The tense meal culminates in a physical fight, during which Michelle stabs Teddy with a fork. They are interrupted by Casey visiting the farmhouse, investigating Michelle's phone signal, which was detected in the area. Don takes Michelle back to the basement at gunpoint while Teddy distracts Casey by showing him his apiary (beehives), which he has accused Michelle and the Andromedans of diminishing. Michelle offers to help Don avoid convictions if he releases her and surrenders Teddy. Don seemingly agrees before suddenly shooting himself in the head, committing suicide with the shotgun. Hearing the gunshot, Teddy releases the honeybees, which sting Casey, and he is bludgeoned to death with a shovel. When he returns to the basement and finds Don dead, Teddy becomes frantic and grabs the gun, accusing her of manipulating him. Michelle tells Teddy there is a special Andromedan chemical medicine, in a container labelled antifreeze, in her car, which can cure and wake Sandy. Teddy grabs the container and rushes to the hospital to inject it into Sandy's IV bag. While Teddy inadvertently kills his mother, Michelle frees herself. Trying to find a way out of the basement, she discovers Teddy has abducted and killed a few other people he suspected of being aliens. When Teddy returns to the house, Michelle is furious and demands to know how many people killed were truly aliens. She decides to tell him everything about her alien race (it is unclear if she has fabricated it or not, but he listens intently). She explains that the Andromedans came to Earth in the time of the dinosaurs and accidentally killed them. Feeling remorse, the aliens created a new species to populate Earth, which evolved into humans. But humans displayed the worst tendencies of violence, greed and control, which overtook them. The experiments on Sandy were intended to help humans evolve into the next stage of the Andromedan plans. She agrees to arrange the meeting between Teddy and the Andromedans at Auxolith headquarters. They arrive at the office, with all the workers confused about Michelle's sudden reappearance after being missing. In her private office, Teddy reveals he is wearing a suicide vest, and the workers call the police. Michelle appears to use an access code, using a device disguised as a calculator, and instructs Teddy to enter her closet, claiming that it will transport him to her ship. As Michelle \"activates\" the teleporter, the suicide vest detonates, killing Teddy and knocking Michelle unconscious. Michelle wakes in an ambulance on the night of the lunar eclipse. She jumps out of the ambulance and returns to her office, entering the closet with Teddy's remains inside. Suddenly, she is teleported onto the Andromedan mothership, revealing she is the Andromedan empress. After consulting with her fellow citizens, she concludes that the human experiment is a failure beyond hope and decides Earth should be obliterated. In the end, Michelle pops a bubble over a model of Earth, causing every human being on Earth to die instantly. A devastated Michelle gazes out at the dead planet as bees slowly return. Also starring Cedric Dumornay as Chris, Parvinder Shergill as the Doctor, Teneisha Ellis as the Detective, Roger Carvalho as the Young Detective, and journalist/anchorwoman Fredricka Whitfield as herself. It should be mentioned that the title is a Greek word that refers to a ritual or belief about bees spontaneously coming out of carcasses and the collapse of bee colonies (which makes sense for the ending as well). Stone is interesting as the shackled ruthless businesswoman who may or may not be an extra-terrestrial, Plemons is convincing as the highly paranoid nutter, Delbis gets his moments as the slobby neurodivergent cousin, and Silverstone is alright in her supporting role. The direction of Lanthimos is stylish, the cinematography and editing add to the weird atmosphere, as with the original film it plays with the strangeness, being both dark and occasionally funny, and you really don't know where it's going until the bizarre and unforgettable conclusion (the dead bodies all over the world instead of the Earth exploding is a clever devastating touch); it might not be to everyone's tastes, but I found it an interesting absurdist black comedy. Good!"}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9520fb8d-5a8e-4948-be4e-d369aaa76e81", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "f9966d8024de67e5692b37c57529c8d72c39bb55d3789857e8dd14f302103df0"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "Hakihiko", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-28", "title": null, "content": "\"Bugonia\" is another wildly distinctive entry in Yorgos Lanthimos' filmography-a director who has made \"the brilliantly bizarre\" his signature. Here, he does it again with remarkable confidence. The film is weird in all the right ways: unsettling, darkly humorous, and layered with that peculiar emotional distance that gradually becomes its own form of intimacy.\n\nThe performances are stellar across the board. The actors sink into the film's odd rhythms and offbeat tone with total commitment, making every awkward pause, clipped line, or deadpan exchange feel magnetic. It's the kind of movie where the performances don't just elevate the material-they're inseparable from the film's identity.\n\nTonally and thematically, \"Bugonia\" reaches into the same orbit as \"The Lobster\". It has that same absurdist edge mixed with a quietly sharp commentary, the kind that reveals more the longer you sit with it. While it forges its own path, you can feel the familiar Lanthimos pulse beneath the surface: precise, haunting, and strangely captivating.\n\nIt's a great, weird movie-one that embraces its strangeness fully and rewards anyone willing to follow its peculiar logic."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "9e93bf0c-91ca-41ca-a2e4-9ba0ddeb6f68", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "01b39260ccbb3c0118b101669ddbd92a01d6820bdf97a8a2f7a5a65d3752469d"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "planktonrules", "rating": 6, "date": "2025-10-31", "title": null, "content": "\"Bugonia\" is a remake of a Korean movie, \"Save the Green Planet\". Both are enjoyable and worth seeing...though I must caution you: It is a VERY bloody and depressing film.\n\nThe story is about a weirdo and his cousin who kidnap a high-profile career woman. Why? Well, it ain't for money. Instead, they are convinced that she is an alien...and they must break her and convince her to take her to her mothership to convince the aliens to leave the Earth in peace.\n\nThe film is very violent and not exactly original, as the Korean version came out some time ago. It is well made and I applaud Emma Stone for going all-in for the role...including shaving off her hair and looking about as unglamourous as possible. It is worth seeing...but I can't see a reason to see the American version when a perfectly good Korean version is out there and has been since 2003."}}
{"metadata": {"ingestion_id": "ea53cffc-f388-4f03-9d69-6f7e30a14d3b", "source_system": "imdb", "entity": "reviews", "extraction_method": "Scraping", "ingestion_timestamp": "2026-03-12T00:07:28.188446", "http_status": 200, "search_parameters": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "count": 100}, "raw_hash": "6443b17f2c066df396aff459ca75e696bd6f1d9050ee512142dbc315843f4066"}, "raw_payload": {"movie_id": "tt12300742", "author": "PWray_99", "rating": 8, "date": "2025-11-18", "title": null, "content": "Bugonia is an English remake of a South Korean film called Save the Green Planet!. The movie follows around two conspiracy theorists who kidnap a powerful CEO they believe is an alien sent to destroy the Earth. Directed by Yorgos Lanthimos known for his wackiness and yeah this movie gets pretty wacky. This is definitely Jesse Plemons's movie as he plays the lead conspirator. He is such a great actor and you really get sucked into his crazy conspiracy especially when you start to see his tragic backstory. His character is extremely complicated and his scenes with Emma Stone are great. They are both great actors so their back and forth are great throughout. I really liked this movie. The only complaint I have is with its ending as I understood the message it was going for but I also do have some issues with some of the story at the same time. It is more of a personal nitpick than anything. It is weird so it is not for everyone but if you had this on your radar, go see it."}}
